<FIRST>r a AM-SubmarineFire     05-27 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Submarine Fire,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Disables Sub Off Southern California Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engine room fire forced an attack submarine
to surface off the Southern California coast, and the
diesel-powered sub was towed to San Diego on Friday, Navy officials
said.
   None of the 73 crew members aboard the USS Blueback were injured
in the Thursday afternoon fire, the second accident in two days
involving a San Diego-based submarine.
   Another ship was towing the Blueback to San Diego, said Lt.
Sonya Hedley, a spokeswoman for the Naval Submarine Base here.
Officers initially had hoped the sub could make the trip under its
own power.
   ``They experienced a minor electrical fire in their propulsion
system,'' Hedley said. The sub, which carries a crew of 65 enlisted
and eight officers, was on general training operations, she said.
   In the other incident, the attack submarine Gurnard was freed
after being stuck on a reef for about four hours. The ship was
submerged when it hit the reef, Ms. Hedley said, correcting earlier
reports it was on the surface.
   No injuries were reported among the Gurnard's 135-man crew, the
Navy spokeswoman said, and the grounding was under investigation by
Rear Admiral David Oliver, who is commander of the San Diego-based
Submarine Group Five.
</TEXT>
