<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0724 05-27 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0724,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Go Back to School After Strike Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `Attendance figures...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with attendance figures on students and teachers. Picks up 10th graf pvs,
`On Thursday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers and students returned to peaceful
campuses Friday after settlement of a nearly two-week strike, but
the atmosphere was more social than academic, some said.
   ``People haven't seen each other in two weeks and they want to
talk to each other and welcome each other back,'' said 10th Street
Elementary School Assistant Principal Evelyn Peter.
   Throughout the 700-square-mile district, teachers at nearly 600
schools were greeted with flowers, balloons and hugs from students.
But numerous absences indicated the Memorial Day weekend may have
tempted many students to stay away.
   Students who reported to class during the strike were subjected
to auditorium assemblies, educational films and lengthy study
periods overseen by substitute teachers. Thousands of others stayed
away from school.
   ``I don't think we knew how much our teachers provided us with
motivation to learn,'' said Sam Perez, a senior at Hollywood High
School.
   ``Everything is back to normal now,'' said a smiling Brenda
Montoya, a 10th grader at Belmont High School. ``We have our
teachers back and now we can get back to our studies.''
   Special education teacher Russell Ung said the mood among the
teachers was upbeat at Belmont High. ``It seems to be getting back
to normal. From everyone I've talked to, the mood is good, the
attitude is excellent,'' he said.
   But he noticed that classes seemed thin. ``Some may be taking
advantage of the long weekend,'' he said.
   There were 365,137 students in class in the nation's second
largest school district, hardly a dramatic lift from the 305,650
attending Thursday, the last day of the strike that began May 15.
   Teachers did return nearly in force, with 24,569 regularly
assigned teachers out of a possible 26,250 returning Friday, with
1,447 substitutes bringing the number to 26,016, ``pretty close to
full strength,'' said school district spokeswoman Eva Hain.
   On Thursday, members of United Teachers-Los Angeles approved by
voice vote a $600 million, three-year contract giving them a 24
percent raise over three years and a bigger voice in the control of
their schools.
   The Los Angeles Unified School District's seven-member board
approved the pact during a closed door meeting the same day, with
arguments centering on the $120 million in cuts the school board
staff says will have to be made elsewhere to provide the teacher
salary increases. The contract, 16 months in the making, is
retroactive to July.
   The union represents 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers,
counselors, nurses and librarians.
</TEXT>
