<FIRST>r a PM-MarijuanaRally     05-27 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marijuana Rally,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Marijuana Group Agrees to Parking Lot Rally Without Rock Music</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They can't play rock music, and they
have to use a parking lot, instead of a ballfield. But a
pro-marijuana group has won a judge's permission to hold a rally
over the Memorial Day weekend.
   U.S. District Judge Frank Freedman on Friday ordered the
Massachusetts Cannabis Reform Coalition to refrain from selling
T-shirts or playing amplified music at the rally Sunday in North
Adams, a small industrial city in the Berkshires.
   A rock concert would not be in keeping with the ``solemnity of
Memorial Day, when we acknowledge those who died representing their
country,'' the judge said.
   He also pointed out that ``the Constitution protects expressions
of thought, not profit-making activities.''
   Richard Evans, an attorney for the group, said it was willing to
use the parking lot, rather than a ballfield as it had originally
hoped.
   ``It's a disappointment, but we'll have speeches, acoustic music
and distribute literature,'' said Curt Mansfield, one of the
organizers, after the hearing in U.S. District Court in Springfield.
   On Wednesday, the judge told both sides to find a suitable place
for the rally. Mayor John Barrett III, who opposes legalization,
suggested the city landfill.
   ``This group has a right to express its feelings whether we
agree with them or not,'' Freedman said Friday, noting that the
coalition's request had been before the city Recreation Commission
for four months.
   Mansfield said the group initially wanted to march in the city's
Memorial Day Parade, but a Vietnam veterans group opposed the idea.
   ``They wanted no part of it,'' he said. ``So we came up the idea
of having a gathering in the park.''
   Said Evans: ``We recognize that reform of the marijuana laws is
a very controversial subject. And we were hesitant to inject it
into the Memorial Day Parade because of the solemnity of the
observance.''
</TEXT>
