<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--TobaccoBan     05-27 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Tobacco Ban,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch City to Ban Tobacco Ads</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bellm is CQ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tobacco ads will be banned from
public billboards in this city of 450,000 in a bid to combat
tobacco-related diseases, a municipal official said.
   ``We think tobacco is such a threat to public health that steps
should be taken quickly,'' spokesman Andy Bellm said Friday.
   Under a city plan, the ads will be banned from The Hague's 250
advertising billboards after renewal of their annual lease
contracts, he said. Bellm said the tobacco ads, on about two-thirds
of the public advertising space, bring in $90,000 a year.
   He noted that in 1986, about 800 people in the city of 450,000
succumbed to tobacco-related diseases such as lung cancer, heart
attacks and respiratory problems. That was the latest year for
which figures are available.
   The Dutch government is considering extending a nationwide ban
on tobacco promotion on radio and television to a more
comprehensive one.
</TEXT>
