<FIRST>r a PM-Names     05-27 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Johnny Paycheck
will perform for his fellow inmates at an Ohio prison next month,
and ex-convict Merle Haggard will join him.
   Paycheck and Haggard will perform two concerts June 13 at the
Chillicothe Correctional Institution, said warden Arthur Tate Jr.
   ``We're excited about the opportunity to put on something like
this,'' Tate said. ``This has the makings of something really big.''
   Paycheck, 50, is serving a seven- to 9{-year sentence for
shooting a man in a southern Ohio bar in 1985. Paycheck is best
known for his 1978 hit song, ``Take This Job and Shove It.''
   Haggard, one of country music's top singers for the past 25
years, spent three years in San Quentin Prison for burglarizing a
cafe. He was paroled in 1960 and pardoned in 1972 by
then-California Gov. Ronald Reagan.
   The prison concert will be recorded for release as an album,
tentatively called ``Behind the Walls,'' Billy Don Burns,
Paycheck's record producer in Nashville, said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROGERSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dolly Parton's younger sister,
singer-actress Stella Parton, says people always ask her what it's
like to be in the shadows of a country music legend.
   ``I don't know what to compare it to,'' she said. ``I've always
been her sister since the day I was born.''
   Miss Parton, 40, prefers to focus on her own career, which
includes spending 200 days on the road each year. She runs her own
record and production companies from Nashville. She began singing
with her sisters at age 7, but she has yet to score a big hit.
   ``I'm not one to wince at a challenge,'' Miss Parton said. ``My
recording career has been slow to take off at times, but I found I
was quite good at doing other things and I also enjoyed it.''
   Miss Parton appeared in the television show ``The Dukes of
Hazzard'' and on stage in ``The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas''
and ``Pump Boys and Dinettes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dustin Hoffman will not pay any money
to the estate of a woman who accidentally died on the actor's
estate in 1986.
   A settlement was reached Thursday in a lawsuit against Hoffman
and three other defendants that stemmed from the drowning of Sheila
Cruse Fionda.
   ``The amount will not be disclosed but the settlement does not
involve any money from Mr. Hoffman,'' said Superior Court Judge
Walter M. Pickett Jr. The case was to go to trial Thursday.
   The lawsuit, filed by Fionda's former husband on behalf of their
son, concerned claims of wrongful death and negligence in Fionda's
Aug. 24, 1986, drowning. Hoffman was not at the estate at the time.
   Fionda, 43, a teacher, was found about 6 a.m. in the hot tub
portion of a swimming pool on Hoffman's Roxbury estate. An autopsy
showed her blood-alcohol count was three times the legal limit for
drunken driving in Connecticut.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Miss America Bess Myerson's boyfriend has
left the Allenwood federal prison in Pennsylvania for a halfway
house in New York City to finish serving his sentence for tax
evasion.
   Carl Capasso, 47, owner of a sewer construction company, is due
for release June 26 after completing two years of a three-year
sentence.
   Inmates awaiting release live in the halfway house, but go to
work during the day and may receive weekend passes.
   Capasso was jailed in 1987 after pleading guilty to evading
nearly $1.5 million in taxes.
   Miss Myerson later was forced to leave her post as the city's
cultural affairs commissioner after taking the Fifth Amendment
before the grand jury that investigated Capasso.
   Later, she was accused of having used her city job to try to
influence a judge handling Capasso's divorce case. She was
acquitted of charges that she gave the judge's daughter a job in
return for rulings that reduced Capasso's support and child care
payments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., has been released
from the hospital where he had been treated since May 9 for
pneumonia and symptoms associated with Parkinson's disease, an aide
said.
   Udall, 66, has had Parkinson's disease for about 10 years and
periodically goes into the hospital to have his medication
adjusted. During a visit this month, doctors discovered he had
pneumonia, said his chief of staff, Matt James.
   James said Udall is fully recovered from the pneumonia but is
supposed to rest at his home in Arlington, Va., next week.
   Udall, a 15-term congressman, is chairman of the House Interior
and Insular Affairs Committee.
