<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina     05-27 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentines Loot Supermarkets; Police Deployed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarkets in at least four
cities were looted and one was set afire in unrest prompted by high
inflation. No injuries were reported, but more than 90 people were
arrested.
   Police in central Cordoba, Argentina's second-biggest city, were
deployed at public buildings and radio and TV stations as well as
supermarkets to ward off incidents, police and Argentine media
reported. They said authorities seized firebombs.
   In Mendoza, 620 miles west of Buenos Aires, a supermarket was
set ablaze Friday by firebombs, the news agencies Diario y Noticias
and Noticias Argentinas reported.
   In the working class towns of Quilmes to the south and Mataderos
to the west, food stores and delivery trucks were robbed, the news
agencies said.
   Police and the news agencies reported 60 arrests in Cordoba,
about 25 in Mataderos and six in Quilmes.
   In Buenos Aires on Friday night, about 300 women demanding wage
increases and an end to recent price rises banged pots and pans
outside Government House.
   Inflation is projected to top 70 percent this month, wages have
shrunk by more than 30 percent this year and people are hungry
across this country that exports huge quantities of grain and beef.
   ``What I spent to buy five bottles of cooking oil last month
won't buy even one now,'' said Elsa de Bermudez, a housewife at the
rally in Buenos Aires.
   ``My husband works two jobs and earns about 5,000 australs'' a
month, or about $25, she said. ``It's humiliating. It makes me
sick.''
   President Alfonsin's governing Radical Civic Union lost
elections May 14 to the Peronist Party in large part because of the
deteriorating economy. Alfonsin offered to step down before
scheduled on Dec. 10; President-elect Carlos Menem declined to take
office early.
   The Argentine currency has been devalued by 90 percent against
the dollar since February. Bus and commuter train, gas,
electricity, telephone and other public utility rates were
increased sharply last week.
   Exchange houses were closed since Monday in an effort to reduce
speculation against the austral. Banks, which fear a run on
deposits, were closed Monday and Tuesday but resumed some
transactions Wednesday. The limit for withdrawals is 20,000
australs every two days, or about $100.
   Looting of supermarkets, butcher shops, food stores and delivery
trucks _ and clashes with police, who have fired tear gas and
rubber bullets _ began Tuesday. Some hungry looters have eaten food
on the spot.
   The government attributes the incidents to agitators that so far
it has refused to identify. ``There is no doubt'' that the looters
are organized, said Facundo Suarez, chief of the state intelligence
agency.
   Alfonsin reportedly was set to address the nation Sunday to
announce details of a new anti-inflation program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
