<FIRST>r a PM-Nancy'sCenter Bjt   05-27 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nancy's Center, Bjt,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Just Says No to Plans for Drug Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing concerns of residents fearful of crime
and addicts in their neighborhoods, former first lady Nancy Reagan
just said no to plans for a drug rehabilitation center that would
bear her name.
   Mrs. Reagan cited local concerns for her decision to abandon the
$10 million Nancy Reagan Center for Drug Rehabilitation, a
spokesman said Friday.
   ``There is a God. I'm on the verge of tears,'' said Lew Snow,
vice president of the Lake View Terrace Homeowners Association, the
group opposing the center. ``I think it shows you can beat city
hall.
   ``Despite all the pressures that people with money and power can
put on a mixed community of all races and incomes, they can still
pull together to defend themselves and win.''
   Residents of the rustic Lake View Terrace neighborhood 20 miles
northwest of downtown had objected to the drug treatment center,
claiming it could bring crime to the neighborhood and traffic jams
when Mrs. Reagan visited it.
   Phoenix House, which operates 10 drug treatment centers
nationwide, said Mrs. Reagan's decision to withdraw ended its
efforts to take over the closed Lake View Terrace Medical Center,
but indicated another San Fernando Valley location would be sought
to bear Mrs. Reagan's name.
   The former first lady ``has been deeply impressed by many
treatment programs, especially Phoenix House, which enjoys a
well-deserved reputation for excellence,'' Reagan family spokesman
Mark Weinberg said. ``But Mrs. Reagan respects the concerns of
those in the Lake View Terrace neighborhood. She regrets that this
situation has upset members of the community.''
   Mrs. Reagan has continued her ``Just Say No'' anti-drug crusade
since moving back to California earlier this year.
   ``Phoenix House understands Mrs. Reagan's desire to change the
proposed site of the Nancy Reagan Center,'' said spokeswoman Billie
Greer. ``Accordingly we will terminate our agreement to purchase
the former Lake View Medical Center in Lake View Terrace.''
   Greer said the organization remained ``committed to meeting the
treatment needs of young drug abusers in the San Fernando Valley.''
Another location in the area would be sought, she said.
   Snow said he learned of Mrs. Reagan's decision to withdraw
during a meeting with Nancy Reagan Foundation Executive Director
John Gustafson, Reagan chief of staff Fred Ryan, and Howard
Raphael, the lobbyist hired by the Lake View Terrace Homeowners
Association.
   ``We were dumbfounded,'' Snow said. ``Of the 500 things on my
list of things to come up in the meeting, that was not one of
them.''
   On March 8, the proposed drug center had won a conditional use
permit from the Board of Zoning Appeals, which placed strict
security requirements on the site, and a two-year limit to the
operating permit.
   Associate Zoning Administrator Darryl Fisher said then that
Phoenix House would have to erect a seven-foot wrought-iron fence
around the center, maintain a 24-hour guard at the front gate, and
place video surveillance cameras inside the center.
   Phoenix House was to have 210 beds, a residential high school
and treatment center for as many as 150 teen-agers and 60 young
adults.
   Snow said a planned June 4 demonstration in front of the
Reagan's Bel-Air home had been canceled.
   ``We'll probably have some kind of neighborhood rally instead,''
he said.
</TEXT>
