<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     05-27 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Rebel Leader Becomes First To Sign Government Document</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former rebel leader returned home
after more than two years in exile and became the first to sign a
document saying she did not support armed struggle against the
leftist government.
   ``I have been forced to fulfill a requirement in order to be
allowed back into my own country,'' Azucena Ferrey, a former member
of the Nicaraguan Resistance directorate, said upon her return
Friday.
   ``But the struggle of the Nicaraguan people is well worth
bending one's pride.''
   About 40 cheering supporters, most of them from the Democratic
Christian Party, greeted Ms. Ferrey's flight from Costa Rica.
   ``At this time the battlefield is on the political field,'' Ms.
Ferrey said when asked if her return meant she had cut ties to the
rebels, known as Contras.
   The U.S.-backed rebels have fought the leftist Sandinista
government since 1981. In August 1987, the five Central American
presidents signed a peace plan whose provisions include an end to
insurgencies in the region and to outside aid to rebel groups.
   Adan Fletes of the Social Christian Party was among those who
greeted Ms. Ferrey at the airport. Ms. Fletes said she would run
for a National Assembly seat in general elections scheduled for
February 1990.
   Ms. Fletes also said she will participate in a march organized
by 15 political parties and opposition labor groups set for Sunday
in Masaya.
   Ms. Ferrey said she planned to stay in Nicaragua about a week
but intended to return to Nicaragua permanently.
   Also Friday, wildcat strikes by teachers demanding higher pay
waned after the government expelled two U.S. diplomats, accusing
them and right-wing parties of instigating the walkouts.
   The government said Thursday that the diplomats attended teacher
meetings in Chinandega the day before and promised money to
encourage strikes. The U.S. Embassy denied the charges.
</TEXT>
