<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     05-27 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petition By Older Pilots Denied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has denied
a petition from a group of older pilots seeking permission to fly
after age 60, saying older pilots are more likely to be involved in
accidents.
   The agency announced, however, that it would fund a detailed
study of pilot age and accident rates and indicated it might be
willing to certify individual pilots over 60 if a way can be found
to determine their capacities.
   ``What is needed and what the petitioners have failed to show,''
the FAA said Friday, ``is a way to discriminate between those who
contribute to the adverse trend of increasing accidents (involving
older pilots) and those who do not.''
   The FAA said it is willing to look at any scientific evidence
that will help in setting criteria for selecting older pilots who
have a low accident risk.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Supplemental Housing Allowance Readjusted by Pentagon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced it has readjusted a key
supplemental housing allowance and more than 800,000 people in the
military services will see a small increase in that part of their
paycheck.
   The change in the variable housing allowance, set to begin June
1, will be the second increase this year.
   The Pentagon declined to estimate the average increase on a
percentage basis, saying all the geographic factors hadn't been
computed. But figures released by the Defense Department suggest
the increase will exceed this year's first hike of 3.4 percent, and
will range from an average $4.80 a month extra for a private to
$13.01 a month extra for a colonel.
   Military officials boosted the allowance in January,
deliberately holding down the size of that hike to make sure the
Pentagon didn't exceed a congressional limit of $1.22 billion for
the entire program.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Arizona Congressman Released from Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., was released from
the hospital where he had been treated since May 9 for pneumonia
and symptoms associated with Parkinson's disease, an aide said.
   Udall, 66, has had Parkinson's disease for about 10 years and
periodically goes into the hospital to have his medication
adjusted. During a routine visit this month, doctors discovered he
had pneumonia, his chief of staff, Matt James, said Friday.
   James said Udall is fully recovered from the pneumonia but is
supposed to rest at his home in Arlington, Va., next week. Udall, a
15-term congressman, is chairman of the House Interior and Insular
Affairs Committee.
