<DOCNO> AP890527-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 0357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Drought     05-27 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Drought,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Too Late To Save Crop</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TARAGANJ, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain has ended a three-month
drought, but it came too late to save much of the rice that most of
this impoverished nation's 110 million people rely upon, farmers
and officials said.
   ``Last week's rain should have come at least a month ago. Now
there is water, but the damage is already done,'' said Abdul Jalil,
a farmer who has to feed 24 people in his family.
   Agriculture officials said the rain can save only 40 percent of
the rice crop near this village about 130 miles northwest of Dhaka.
In some areas the loss is estimated at 80 percent, the officials
said on condition of anonymity.
   Jalil planted rice on the two acres he owns and was planning to
sell the expected harvest of 22,800 pounds.
   ``But this year I will have to buy rice from the market to feed
my family,'' he said, sitting at the edge of his withered rice
paddies.
   Jalil, 40, said he was still trying to repay a bank loan taken
to offset losses during last summer's floods.
   The deluge inundated four-fifths of Bangladesh, killing at least
1,400 people and destroying 2.5 million tons of rice and wheat.
   Bangladesh, one of the poorest countries in the world with
annual per capita income of $160, alternates between flood and
drought. These and other natural disasters such as tornadoes and
cyclones have crippled government efforts to improve the economy.
   Almost 80 percent of the population depends on agriculture. In
good years, the country produces about 17 million of the 18.5
million tons of grain needed to feed itself. The rest is imported.
   Economists fear this year's drought will prompt a food shortage.
   ``Though the government claims it has adequate food stock, we
are apprehensive. The effect of drought on the economy is going to
be significant,'' said Khwaja Shamsul Huq, head of he Association
of Development Agencies in Bangladesh.
   The group is a coalition of more than 100 local and foreign
non-government organizations.
   The government says it has a food grain reserve of 800,000 tons
and plans to import 2 million tons more.
   Agriculture Ministry officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said last year's flood and the current drought may push
the deficit to 3 million tons.
   The officials said 80 percent of the shallow wells in the area
had run dry. Deep wells, reaching nearly 500 feet underground,
still functioned, but these accounted for only 10 percent of the
total wells.
   Sheikh Surat Ali, another Taraganj farmer, said his village had
only one pump to operate wells that irrigate more than 40 acres.
``But that also did not work'' for most of April.
   ``Today I got water but it will be 15 days before my next
turn,'' Ali said, wiping his brow with his tattered sarong. He said
50 farmers share the pump.
   Officials and economists say relying on deep wells also lowers
the water table.
   A National Disaster Planning Council has discussed building
canals for more water. It also wants to improve techniques to
evacuate people during floods. But the plan has a $7 billion price
tag and the government is seeking foreign donations to implement it.
   ``We are tied in a vicious circle. Flooding this year, drought
next year. It seems we have no escape from natural disasters,'' a
Planning Ministry official said on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0034 </DOCNO>
