<FIRST>r a PM-SliceofAmerica     05-27 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slice of America,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreigners Treated To An Evening of Americana</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ULA ILNYTZKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Katarina is a Pole by birth who adopted Sweden
as her home, but at an all-American hot dog and apple pie Memorial
Day event she conceded she feels most at home here where she can be
``free, free, free.''
   Katarina and about 80 other foreigners were treated to a slice
of Americana on the eve of a three-day holiday weekend in which
Americans remember their war servicemen.
   The Friday night event was anything but somber, however.
   In fact, it could easily have been called corny except for the
fact that these foreigners beamed with patriotic pride as they
belted out ``Yankee Doodle,'' ``When Johnny Comes Marching Home,''
and other familiar American tunes.
   The Memorial Day festival _ complete with hot dogs and beans,
coleslaw, real lemonade, and apple pie _ took place in the concrete
jungle of Manhattan. The group enthusiastically swayed and members
clapped their hands as the Pep Boys band gave a sampling of
bluegrass.
   Stockholm, where Katarina lived for 20 years, ``is clean,
beautiful, safe and b-o-r-i-n-g,'' she said. In New York, ``you can
find people on the streets all night.''
   What about the crime?
   ``Crime is everywhere. Eight million people live in Sweden and
eight million people live in New York. I'm sure as much crime
occurs in all of Sweden as in New York,'' she replied.
   ``I can be free, free, free'' here, she said.
   The International Center in New York is a non-profit group that
provides educational services and cultural programs to about 3,000
foreigners annually.
</TEXT>
