<FIRST>r a PM-LukensTrial     05-27 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens Trial,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Convicted of Sex Charge; Aide Vows `We Will Be Running'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. congressman convicted of having sex
with a 16-year-old girl will run for re-election despite a call for
his resignation from a fellow representative, an aide said.
   Rep. Donald Lukens, R-Ohio, ``will be spending some quiet time,
speaking to family and friends to get a lot of opinion and advice.
But I'll say this, we will be running,'' said Lukens' chief of
staff, William Jarrell.
   Lukens was convicted Friday of contributing to the delinquency
and unruliness of a minor after a Franklin County Domestic Court
jury deliberated for an hour and a half. Lukens faces a maximum
sentence on the misdemeanor charge of 180 days in jail and a $1,000
fine.
   Within an hour after the conviction, the senior Republican of
Ohio's congressional delegation called for Lukens to step down.
   ``I think he should do the gentlemanly thing and resign,'' said
Rep. Chalmers Wylie.
   Lukens showed no expression during the reading of the verdict.
He declined comment before leaving the courthouse. Jarrell said
Lukens plans a statement next week.
   Lukens, 58, who is divorced, was indicted on Feb. 23 after a
Columbus television station broadcast a secretly recorded videotape
that apparently showed Lukens offering to find the girl's mother a
job.
   The charge stemmed from an Nov. 6 incident at Lukens' apartment
in which 16-year-old Rosie Coffman was paid $40 to have sex him.
   Neither Miss Coffman nor her mother, Anna Coffman, was in the
courtroom when the verdict was read. Mrs. Coffman also testified.
   Mrs. Coffman, Lukens' chief accuser, testified that Lukens
offered to find her a government job after she accused him of
having sex with her daughter. The meeting between Lukens and Mrs.
Coffman at a Columbus fast-food restaurant on Nov. 11, 1988, was
videotaped by television station WSYX. Mrs. Coffman had called the
station with her story.
   Miss Coffman said she was pleased with the verdict.
   ``I'm happy to see justice is done,'' she said.
   Lukens' attorney, Thomas Tyack, said Lukens will appeal the
verdict.
   Sentencing was delayed pending completion of a presentence
investigation.
</TEXT>
