<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 0553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UnmarkedQuarters     05-27 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unmarked Quarters,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Collectors' Item? _ Quarters With No Mint Mark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coin experts say some 1989 quarters could be
worth hundreds of dollars because the U.S. Mint unwittingly struck
an unknown number of them with no mint mark.
   Readers of the Numismatic News, a weekly coin collector's
publication based in Iola, Wis., sent in two 1989 quarters missing
the mint mark, The New York Times reported today.
   A spokesman for Stack's, a New York coin dealer, said the 1989
quarter could be worth $250 to $1,000, based on prices of other
coins with similar errors.
   All of the 605.9 million 1989 quarters already minted should
bear a mark just to the right of the George Washington's head that
tells where the coin was minted. A ``P'' indicates the mint at
Philadelphia and a ``D'' the Denver mint. Quarters minted in
Philadelphia before 1980 do not have a mint mark.
   The first quarter sent to Numismatic News also had the second 9
in 1989 partly erased.
   Eugene H. Essner, the deputy director of the U.S. Mint, analyzed
the first quarter and confirmed that it was genuine. If it had been
tampered with in an effort to remove the mark, a microscopic
inspection would show signs of metal deformation, he said.
   The last such error with a mint mark came on some 1982 dimes,
which are now worth about $140 each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
