<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strike South; Rivers Overflow in Ohio, Indiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the mid-Atlantic
states across Kentucky and the lower Mississippi Valley to parts of
the southern Plains early today, while earlier flooding in Ohio
left one child dead.
   A one-lane bridge carrying U.S. 52 over the rain-swollen Great
Miami River at Miamitown, 10 miles west of Cincinnati, collapsed
Friday. Two cars were swept into the river, and all the occupants
were feared dead. Police did not know how many people were in the
vehicles.
   Earlier Friday, rescuers in Camden, Ohio, used lifelines and
boats to lead 30 occupants of a trailer park through chest-high
water to safety. A total of 200 people were forced from their homes
in the town southwest of Dayton.
   A 20-month-old drowned in Donnels Creek near Dayton, the
sheriff's department said.
   Flood warnings were posted for four rivers in Indiana. The
Maumee River was expected to crest 6 feet above flood stage at Fort
Wayne tonight.
   Thunderstorms Friday evening produced damaging winds and large
hail in Tennessee, North Carolina, Oklahoma and Texas.
   A tornado caused minor injuries at Sevierville in eastern
Tennessee. In western Texas, golf ball-size hail pounded McCamey
and walnut-size hail fell near Bakersfield. Hail also fell in parts
of Oklahoma.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over northern Maine and the
northern Pacific Coast.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included nearly an inch at Jackson, Tenn.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over Mississippi, Georgia and the middle Atlantic Coast; widely
scattered showers over the northern Atlantic Coast and the Pacific
Northwest; and showers and a few thunderstorms in Idaho, Montana,
northeast Wyoming and western South Dakota.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s and 60s along much of the
California coast and in the Pacific Northwest, the northern Rockies
and the Great Lakes; in the 90s in southeastern North Carolina,
Florida, southern Louisiana and southern Texas; in the 100s in the
desert Southwest and the Rio Grande Valley in Texas; and in the 70s
and 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., to 84 degrees at Del Rio, Texas, and
Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Boston 68 foggy; Buffalo 53 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 76 foggy; Cincinnati 66 partly cloudy; Cleveland
63 partly cloudy; Detroit 57 partly cloudy; Miami 79 fair; New York
68 foggy; Philadelphia 67 fair; Pittsburgh 64 party cloudy;
Washington 74 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 43 fair; Chicago 54 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
71 cloudy; Denver 52 windy; Des Moines 48 fair; Indianapolis 60
partly cloudy; Kansas City 50 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 46 fair;
Nashville 69 foggy; New Orleans 75 foggy; St. Louis 59 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 65 windy; Anchorage 53 cloudy; Las Vegas 70
fair; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 84 fair; Salt Lake City 53 fair;
San Diego 62 partly cloudy; San Francisco 53 windy; Seattle 50 rain.
