<FIRST>r a PM-HouseLeadership-Foley     05-27 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Leadership-Foley,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Terms Coelho's Departure a Loss for House</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley, the
likely successor to embattled Speaker Jim Wright's post, said the
looming departure of the No. 3 House Democrat will be ``a loss for
the House of Representatives.''
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho has ``had a brilliant record as
chairman of the campaign committee and as the party whip, and I
think he'll be deeply missed by his colleagues and by the
constituents he served so well,'' Foley said of the California
Democrat.
   Coelho told colleagues late Friday that he intends to resign
from Congress next month rather than endure a protracted ethics
investigation. Coelho has come under criticism for his personal
business dealings, particularly the handling of a $100,000
investment in junk bonds.
   Coelho's decision added a new element of uncertainty to the
future makeup of the House leadership. Wright, embroiled in an
ethics controversy of his own, is widely expected to give up his
post next week, and Foley is the favorite to replace him. Coelho
had been expected to be a candidate to replace Foley as majority
leader.
   Foley, a 13-term congressman, declined Friday to answer
questions or speculate on whether he would succeed Wright, should
the Texan resign the speakership.
   Foley said telephone calls and letters from constituents ``are
overwhelmingly about other things,'' such as health care, gun
control and issues other than the ethics controversy.
   Foley repeated that he knew of no plan for Wright to step down
nor any deal in the works that would allow him to do so.
</TEXT>
