<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     05-27 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Takeshita To Back Foreign Minister As Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who says he will
resign to take responsibility for an influence-peddling scandal,
has decided to back Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno as his successor,
news reports said today.
   Nearly all major newspapers carried front-page reports of
Takeshita choosing to support Uno, although most said the situation
remained fluid.
   Uno's appointment would fill a leadership vacuum that has
plagued the governing Liberal Democratic Party since Takeshita
announced last month that he would resign. Many party members
previously mentioned as potential successors were believed tainted
by the scandal.
   Takeshita was believed to have discussed the succession problem
today with party Secretary General Shintaro Abe at a Tokyo
hospital, where Abe is recovering from surgery.
   Takeshita told reporters a choice would not be made until late
next week following discussions with other party elders, Kyodo News
Service and other news reports said.
   Party leaders said Uno emerged as the top contender after talks
on Friday between Takeshita and Masayoshi Ito, chairman of the
Liberal Democrats' policy-making Executive Council, according to
the Asahi, Yomiuri and Mainichi newspapers.
   Uno, 66, a 10-term member of the powerful lower house of
Parliament and foreign minister since 1987, also has held the
international trade and industry portfolio and served as party
deputy secretary general.
   ``We haven't received any word from Tokyo,'' an official at
Uno's office in Moriyama in western Japan said on condition of
anonymity.
   A spokesman for Takeshita refused to comment.
   A Foreign Ministry official said Uno was to leave Sunday for
Paris to attend a meeting of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development. He is to return June 4.
   Party leaders reportedly favor Uno because he has experience in
foreign affairs and apparently is untainted by the Recruit bribery
scandal, which already has led to more than a dozen arrests.
   Uno faces some opposition, however, because he is a leading
member of the Liberal Democratic faction headed by Takeshita's
predecessor, Yasuhiro Nakasone, who testified before parliament
this week about his links to the scandal.
   The Recruit Co., the publishing and information services
conglomerate at the center of the scandal, is accused of trying to
influence government policy by selling underpriced, unlisted shares
in a real estate subsidiary and by doling out millions of dollars
in political contributions.
   The scandal has led to the downfall of three Cabinet ministers
and the arrest of a former chief Cabinet secretary.
   Many governing party members have called it the worst crisis
since the party was founded 34 years ago.
   In the meeting with Ito on Friday, Takeshita agreed to stay on
as prime minister until a successor is found, although on April 25
he vowed to leave when the year's budget cleared parliament. The
budget is due to become law on Sunday.
   The head of the governing party routinely serves as prime
minister because of the party's large majority in both houses of
parliament.
   Ito's refusal May 13 to take the top job created a leadership
vacuum in a governing party desperately in need of a leader with a
clean enough reputation to steer the party out of scandal.
</TEXT>
