<FIRST>r a PM-PipelineExplosion     05-27 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pipeline Explosion,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Focus on Dents in Fuel Pipeline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials investigating a pipeline
explosion that killed at least two people are focusing on dents
that were not discovered in a check of the line made after a train
derailment two weeks earlier.
   Meanwhile, many residents evacuated from the neighborhood on
Thursday were expected to be allowed to return home today. Few
among the estimated 96 displaced families voiced much willingness
to do so.
   ``They told us the gas line was no danger, but you can see for
yourself that this place looks like a bomb exploded,'' said George
Liti, 54, whose 9-year-old son suffered burns in the fire. ``None
of us can ever forget.''
   The pipeline fire destroyed 10 houses across the street from the
vacant lots left after the freight train derailed two weeks ago.
That accident killed four people and destroyed six houses.
   Heavy pieces of debris from the May 12 freight train wreck were
found embedded around the 14-inch diameter line, the closest about
15 inches away, federal investigators announced Friday.
   Federal investigators could not say if the metal fragments found
near the line had caused the rupture, said Jim Kolstad, acting
chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board.
   Surface dents on the steel pipeline range up to about 30 inches
long and 4 inches wide, Kolstad said. The section bearing the
30-inch by 4-inch rupture was being removed for laboratory tests in
Washington.
   A section of the damaged line that was excavated revealed a
blown-out hole, with a dent directly across the gash.
   David Andries, operations manager of Calnev Pipe Line Co., owner
of the line, said the section of pipe where the rupture occurred
wasn't excavated in spot checks of the line for damage caused by
the wreck.
   Instead, holes were dug every 50 feet along the 2,000-foot
stretch of track involved in the derailment to check for damage, he
said. Two larger areas were excavated, including one spot where a
locomotive dug into the ground.
   The fire that raged all day Thursday as unleaded gasoline gushed
from the pipe was so intense that it has been difficult to
identify, or even count, the dead, authorities said.
   The San Bernardino County Coroner's office has identified only
one of the victims so far _ Darie Lee Brown, 54.
</TEXT>
