<FIRST>r a PM-TeamstersTrial     05-27 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Trial,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friedman, Fellow Teamster Leader Fined on Embezzlement Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters international Vice President Harold
Friedman has been fined $35,000 and sentenced to four years of
probation for arranging a ``ghost employee'' scheme in which people
received union pay for little or no work.
   U.S. District Court Judge George W. White also Friday granted
Friedman's request to retain his various union leadership positions
pending an appeal of his conviction on embezzlement and
racketeering charges to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Cincinnati.
   Friedman, 66, held a finger to his lips while White announced
the sentence. The Teamsters official then turned and smiled at
friends and relatives who applauded the sentence.
   Friedman could have been sentenced to 52 years in prison and
fined $70,000.
   A co-defendant, Anthony Hughes, was fined $30,000 and also was
put on probation for four years. He faced a possible 45-year prison
term and $60,000 fine.
   ``Justice really prevailed,'' Hughes said after the sentencing.
``Our appeal will be better.''
   Stephen Jigger, a government prosecutor, declined to comment
after the sentencing. He had asked White to impose a
``substantial'' sentence, saying, ``Harold Friedman abused his
position of trust.''
   Friedman was a longtime ally of former Teamsters international
President Jackie Presser, who had been indicted in the same case
but died before going on trial.
   Friedman and his attorney, Paul Cambria of Buffalo, N.Y., made
an impassioned appeal during a two-hour morning hearing, asking
White to avoid imposing a prison term and to allow Friedman to keep
his union jobs pending appeal.
   Friedman also serves as president of the Ohio Council of
Teamsters, Teamsters Joint Council 41 in northeast Ohio, Teamsters
Local 507 and Bakery Workers Local 19.
   ``I don't believe I did anything dishonest,'' Friedman said.
   Friedman was convicted Jan. 13 of two counts of labor
racketeering, one count of embezzlement and one count of filing
false reports. He was acquitted of one count of embezzlement and
one count of filing false reports.
   Hughes, 52, secretary-treasurer of Local 507, was found guilty
of all charges against him _ two counts of labor racketeering and
one of embezzlement. He was convicted of being a ``ghost employee''
who did no work for the Teamsters union.
</TEXT>
