<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0495 05-27 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network: Grand Jury Probes Possible Clean Water Act Violations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to change overline.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials refused to discuss a
broadcast report that a federal grand jury is investigating
allegations of Clean Water Act violations in the Exxon Valdez oil
spill.
   ``Obviously, one method of investigating would be a grand
jury,'' U.S. Attorney Michael Spaan said Friday. He would not
elaborate in response to questions about the ABC News report.
   Tom Matthews, the FBI's assistant special agent in charge in
Anchorage, said he could ``neither confirm nor deny the workings of
a grand jury.''
   In March, FBI spokesman Bill Carter in Washington said the
agency was focusing on possible felony violations of the Clean
Water Act.
   The FBI said its investigation into the March 24 spill of nearly
11 million gallons of crude oil was continuing in cooperation with
a number of agencies, among them the Coast Guard, the U.S. Fish &amp;
Wildlife Service and the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.
   The Clean Water Act prohibits the willful or negligent discharge
of oil into navigable waters, said Carl Lautenberger, an
environmental protection specialist for the EPA in Anchorage.
   ``The whole jurisdiction for us to write regulations ... to
assess penalities and fines'' is packaged in the act, he said.
   ``It gives federal agencies the jurisdiction to do what they
do.''
   Matthews said the FBI's investigation will be lengthy. He said
he could not specify a time frame.
   ``We're just beginning, really,'' he said.
   Exxon has taken responsibility for the damage that occurred when
its tanker hit a charted reef in Prince William Sound, but has
insisted the company was not negligent in its safety precautions.
</TEXT>
