<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 0913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-WeeklyWallStreet     05-27 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions May 27-28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street's Hope for Summer: Easier Credit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hopes are spreading on Wall Street that
investors will get invited to a financial party this summer catered
by the Federal Reserve.
   The festivities would have a simple theme: Lower interest rates
and higher stock prices, courtesy of an easier credit policy from
the Fed.
   Talk of such a celebration has been increasing for some time
now, ever since signs began to show up that the economy was
beginning to slow.
   Inflation, the target of the Fed's long credit-tightening
campaign from early 1988 through the first couple of months of this
year, hasn't been quite so cooperative.
   To judge from the latest readings, it's still running at a 5
percent to 6 percent annual rate that government officials, and a
good many other observers, consider troublesome.
   But optimists in the financial world still seem willing to bet
that a slower pace of business will sooner or later ease upward
pressure on the cost of living.
   Conjecture about a change of course at the Fed has also been
fanned lately by the sharp rise of the dollar in foreign exchange.
   Presumably, a sustained advance in the dollar would be unwelcome
in policymaking circles, because it would threaten to reverse the
difficult progress that has been made toward shrinking the nation's
trade deficit.
   So far, efforts to keep the dollar stable have consisted mainly
of intervention by the Fed and other banks in the foreign exchange
markets.
   If that proves insufficient, the reasoning goes, the Fed might
want to lower interest rates in this country to reduce the flow of
international funds into dollars.
   For the moment, the dollar's strength seems to have worked in
the U.S. markets' favor.
   ``Whether this marks a major turn in the dollar remains to be
seen,'' said Martin Zweig in his investment advisory letter The
Zweig Forecast.
   ``However, in recent days there has been a sharp pickup in
foreign demand for U.S. stocks as those abroad fear they may miss
the boat on the dollar.''
   The 6-month-old rally in stock prices leveled off in the past
week. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had climbed
119.14 points over the two preceding weeks, slipped back 7.33 to
2,493.77.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index edged up .39 to
179.31; the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
rose 3.16 to 445.21, and the American Stock Exchange market value
index was up 1.18 at 355.01.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 169.79 million shares a day,
against 192.71 million the week before.
   As popular as it may have become, the belief that the Fed is
succeeding in curbing inflation without tipping the economy into a
recession is not yet universally embraced on Wall Street.
   ``To an economist, the main problem with the soft landing
hypothesis is that it is hard to understand the practical mechanics
of slowing growth enough to lower inflation without creating the
stress of a recession first,'' said Robert Brusca at Nikko
Securities International.
   ``In fact, our experience with such happy events is almost
completely lacking.''
   Said Hugh Johnson at First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y., ``the
trend in stock and bond prices is positive. This is being driven by
some measure of speculation in the dollar, which has been
transmitted to our stock and bond markets. This can change.
   ``The current forecast of a soft landing, which is driving the
dollar and the stock and bond markets, may change. It may change at
a time when the stock market is perhaps `overvalued,' and therefore
vulnerable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 0935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Coelho-Text     05-27 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho-Text,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-House Leadership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of a statement issued today
by Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., announcing his resignation as House
majority whip and from Congress:
   For nearly 25 years, I have devoted my life to public service --
first as a congressional staffer, then as congressman, campaign
committee chair, and majority whip. All that time, I have worked
for social change, for wider acceptance of the disabled, for the
interests of my district, and to serve the Democratic Party.
   In recent weeks, my ability to complete those missions has been
diminished by needless and baseless charges about my investments or
private life. I have simply spent too much time building the party
and trying to help people to have my attention or abilities devoted
to such distractions.
   Accordingly, I will not seek the office of majority leader.
Instead, I will tender my resignation as majority whip, and will
also resign my seat in Congress _ on my (47th) birthday _ June 15th.
   All week, my colleagues have expressed their confidence in me
and their support for a leader's race. I would have preferred to
land in that race with both feet, and would have had the votes to
win. Moreover, my attorneys remain convinced that a normal business
transaction, admittedly marred by reporting errors, posed no legal
problems for me, and I accept their advice.
   Undoubtedly, some will think this decision was motivated by
weakness in my political standing or my legal position. They are
entitled to their opinion, but they are wrong.
   I want to thank my family, my party and colleagues, my country
and especially my constituents for all the opportunities I have
enjoyed. I particularly want to thank the community of the disabled
for all the strength they've given my for so many years.
   While I will no longer be working in the Congress, Phyllis, my
daughters and I look forward to conquering new horizons. I always
have, and we always will.
</TEXT>
