<SECOND>PM-Israel-Attack, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0492,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Killed, Two Israeli Soldiers Wounded In Border Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Jordan saying attacker may have been
disturbed Jordanian who abandoned his post. TRIMS. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed a guerrilla
today after he opened fire from the Jordanian side of the border,
the army said. Two soldiers were slightly wounded, it said.
   Jordan, in an official broadcast, suggested the attacker was a
distraught Jordanian soldier who had abandoned his observation post
at the border.
   The attack occurred about 6:30 a.m. near the kibbutz, or
communal settlement, of Hamadiya, the military command said.
Hamadiya is 50 miles northeast of Jerusalem.
   The Israeli army said one of its patrols near a border fence
``encountered light weapons fire from east of the fence'' and
returned fire.
   Soldiers searched the area after the firefight and found the
body of a guerrilla dressed in a military-type uniform and armed
with the U.S.-made, M-16 assault rifle, an army spokesman said.
   The body was found on the Jordanian side of the border, he said.
   Although the army identified the attacker as a guerrilla, the
state-run Jordan Radio quoted an official source as suggesting the
attacker was a Jordanian army soldier.
   ``An official source said today that at 6:30 a.m. the conscript
Issa Mahmoud Ahmad, carrying his gun, abandoned his observation
post at the border,'' the broadcast said.
   ``During search operations for the absent conscript, the sound
of shooting was heard in the Zor Abdullah area northwest of Waqqas
village,'' it said. Waqqas is close to the site of the clash as
given by the Israeli army.
   The Jordanian official was quoted as saying Ahmad ``suffers from
psychological trouble...(and) is still absent.''
   Israel radio gave a different version of the clash, saying that
an army scout was the first to open fire when he heard a noise on
the other side of the border. It said the scout was wounded in the
firefight.
   It was the third infiltration attempt or attack from Jordan
since May 1988.
   ``We have an impression that this is not a new step or a new
direction,'' Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, the head of the army's central
command, told Israel radio in an interview from the site of the
clash.
   ``We see that the Jordanians are making every effort and use all
the means to keep this border secure and closed.''
   In previous cases, Mitzna said, the guerrillas ``succeeded in
sneaking by the Jordanian patrols. This case is still unclear. We
don't know who this man is, where he left from, who sent him and
how he came here.''
   ``We should remember that although Jordan is really trying to
prevent such activity, there is no substitute to our own forces,''
Mitzna said.
</TEXT>
