<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-27 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Summit Causes Few Ripples in Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners shelled the Christian
coastline north of Beirut today despite an appeal by Arab leaders
for a cease-fire.
   A dozen 130mm howitzer shells fired by Syrian gunners from a
battery in Moslem west Beirut slammed into the coast near the
Christian ports of Jounieh and Byblos, a police spokesman said. No
casualties were reported, he said.
   Arab leaders ended a summit in Casablanca, Morocco, on Friday
without a blueprint for solving Lebanon's 14-year civil war or the
recent fighting between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian troops
and his Syrian-Druse foes.
   Fighting broke out again March 8 when Aoun's troops blockaded
illegal Druse-run ports, and the Moslem alliance responded by
shelling the 310-square-mile Christian enclave. Several cease-fires
declared by the Arab League have failed.
   The Arab leaders were unable during their summit to reach an
agreement on proposals to form an observer force for Lebanon.
   Instead, they created a committee of Morocco's King Hassan II,
Saudi monarch King Fahd and Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid to
set up a workable cease-fire over the next six months.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz, who attended the summit,
reported a ``gentleman's agreement'' had been reached calling for
Syria to withdraw its 45,000 troops from Leganon, but there was no
sign it would be honored.
   The committee also is to hammer out a new constitution for
Lebanon.
   Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, was quick to support the summit's resolutions.
   ``I welcome the resolutions of the Arab summit and hope they
will be implemented as soon as possible,'' he said in a statement
released Friday.
   Aoun, who heads the Christian cabinet, has not announced his
position. But the Christian militia was apparently disappointed
because the resolutions did not call openly for the withdrawal of
Syria's troops.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing
to adhere a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League by
siding with the Moslems against the Christians in the civil war.
</TEXT>
