<FIRST>u i AM-MathiasRust Bjt   05-27 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mathias Rust, Bjt,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>Back at Home, Grounded Red Square Pilot Turns Equestrian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEDEL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years after his flight to Red
Square triggered a Kremlin shake-up and drew a Soviet prison
sentence, Mathias Rust's interests are more down to earth. He rides
a horse.
   Back at home in this Hamburg suburb, life is nearly back to
normal for the West German youth who thought his May 28, 1987 stunt
would earn him a meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The crew cut he wore upon release from Moscow's Lefortovo Prison
in August has grown back, as has the grass around his family's
brick apartment house after repeated trampling by journalists and
curiosity seekers.
   But Rust, now 21, has had to change roles from aviator to
equestrian, as local authorities refuse to reinstate his pilot's
license.
   ``I don't like places where there are so many people on so
little space,'' said Rust, seated primly in the tiny dining alcove
cluttered with memorabilia from his moments in the limelight.
``That's why I bought my horse, to get away while I'm not able to
fly.''
   The 8-year-old black mare, Torina, is a champion jumper and was
bought with money Stern magazine paid Rust's family for the rights
to their story.
   The West German press labeled Rust ``the daredevil Kremlin
flier'' when at the age of 19 he flew a single-engine Cessna
through heavily guarded air space and landed in Moscow's Red Square.
   The act was a prelude to the ouster of Soviet Defense Minister
Sergei L. Sokolov and Air Defense chief Alexander Koldunov, because
Soviet air defenses took no action to halt the flight.
   But despite self-confidence about his abilities as an aviator,
Rust is no adventurer and an unlikely hero.
   His political rationale for making the flight has done more to
perplex than impress those who initially took his flight as
reckless derring-do.
   ``It was my direct goal to speak to Gorbachev, to explain that
our people also want better relations. It was impossible at that
time in any other way, so I made the flight,'' Rust said.
   ``I do not regret the flight because in the end, this incident
helped to better relations between East and West and to clarify the
differences and similarities between our societies,'' the
bespectacled youth contended.
   He expresses ``disappointment'' that Gorbachev never granted him
an audience but harbors a hope of meeting him when he travels to
the Soviet Union as a tourist. He cannot get a visa, however, until
his four-year sentence expires in September 1991.
   Rust was convicted in Moscow on charges of violating
international air safety regulations, illegal entry into the Soviet
Union and malicious hooliganism. He was released in August on what
Soviet authorities said were humanitarian grounds.
   He initially faced charges in West Germany, but they were
dropped late last year by the Hamburg state prosecutor's office.
   The sole sanction still in force is the revoked pilot's license.
Rust expects to earn it back some day and fly for one of Hamburg's
air charter services.
   In the meantime, he is spending an idle summer at home with his
parents, Monika and Karl-Heinz, and his 17-year-old brother Ingo.
This fall he will enter the Civilian Service, the pacifist
alternative to West Germany's compulsory military term.
   Rust says his experience in Moscow, where he claims to have
befriended guards, prosecutors and KGB agents, solidified his
opposition to any use of armed force.
   He will instead serve his 20-month term at a local hospital and
get the training he needs to be a health care worker should the
much hoped-for pilot's license not materialize.
   The family's crowded four-room home has been transformed into a
shrine to Rust's crime.
   Photographs, newspaper clippings, artists' sketches and cartoons
lampooning his unauthorized flight from Helsinki to Moscow cover
much of the wall space in the dining and living rooms, as well as
over the bunk beds in what Mrs. Rust still calls ``the children's
room.''
   A poster of Gorbachev has stared across the entrance way since
the first of the family's seven trips to Moscow to visit the jailed
flier.
   Between rides on Torina, stabled at a farm four miles away, Rust
says he is at work on a book and a screenplay that would explain
his Moscow mission.
   The book, progressing slowly, is being penned by hand because
Rust says computers and typewriters are ``intimidating and
overrated.''
   He claims U.S. filmmakers have offered him as much as $500,000
for the movie rights to his story but that he has turned them down
because they would not allow him to write the script.
   His mother claims part of the responsibility for her son's
flight across heavily guarded Soviet territory, recalling how she
would sometimes dream aloud of a Western gesture of peace to the
new Kremlin leader.
   ``But these were just illusions,'' she said. ``I had no idea he
was planning such a thing.''
   Russ contends the idea was his alone and that its roots will
become clear in the book, which he hopes to release some time next
year.
</TEXT>
