<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-BridgeCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0465 05-27 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Collapse Drops at Least Two Vehicles Into River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with 2nd fatality, search resuming;
SUBS 7th graf, `A visual ..., to DELETE outdated reference to search called
off; INSERTS 1 graf after 12th graf, `Divers recovered ..., with details
of 2nd fatality. Pick up 13th graf pvs, `At the ... ' ^LaserPhoto CS2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bridge collapsed minutes after an engineer
recommended closing it, and the rain-swollen river below swept away
at least two vehicles. Flooding elsewhere in Ohio left two people
dead and hundreds out of their homes.
   Police could not say how many people were in the cars, which
plunged into the Great Miami River when a bridge near Miamitown
collapsed Friday evening. Rescuers resumed searching for victims
this morning, but could not enter the flooding river because of its
swift current.
   ``The car in front of us just dropped straight down,'' said
Sharon Boebinger, who was waiting to cross the bridge when it
started collapsing. ``I said, `Oh my God.' I put it in reverse and
backed up. I didn't feel the bridge shake at all. It just happened
in an instant.''
   Lt. Col. Ramon Hoffbauer of the Hamilton County sheriff's office
was asked if anyone could have survived the plunge.
   ``I wouldn't think so,'' he said. ``The current is moving pretty
fast. I can't tell you how fast, but the rescue crews didn't go
into the water at all.''
   The American Red Cross said it got more than a dozen missing
person calls, but Gary Miller, disaster services director, said
none of the missing could be confirmed as river victims.
   Officials said divers likely would have to wait for the water to
recede before going in.
   The collapse of the one-lane, temporary bridge carrying U.S. 52
over the Great Miami River at Miamitown, 10 miles west of
Cincinnati, occurred just 10 minutes after a Hamilton County
engineer had given an order to close the span.
   Widespread flooding in southwestern Ohio earlier Friday sent
people scurrying to rooftops and high ground.
   A couple and their 10-year-old son were stranded on the roof of
their house all day until rescuers reached them by boat, the Butler
County Sheriff's Department said.
   In Camden, rescuers used lifelines and boats to lead 30
occupants of a trailer park through chest-high water to safety. A
total of 200 people were forced from their homes in the town of
about 1,900 people southwest of Dayton.
   Divers recovered the body of 20-month-old Brandon K. Irwin of
Springfield in Donnels Creek, northeast of Dayton, the sheriff's
department said. The boy fell into the swollen creek from a
footbridge near his grandmother's house.
   In Findlay in northwest Ohio, Hancock County sheriff's deputies
recovered the body of Lisa Faust, 24, of Fostoria, from her
overturned car in the Portage River. The car was swept off a county
road by high water, hit a metal bridge abutment and overturned into
the river.
   At the site of the bridge collapse, witnesses gave varying
accounts of two to four vehicles falling into the river, said Bruce
Smith, chief of the Colerain Township Fire Department.
   Radio station WCKY reported at least six people were missing. An
adult and four children were seen in a yellow pickup truck and at
least one person in a car which went under the water, the station
said.
   William Brayshaw, the county's chief deputy engineer, had been
advised by the contractor, National Engineering Co. of
Strongsville, Ohio, that the river was washing tree trunks and
other heavy debris downstream.
   Engineers said the debris posed a threat to the steel beams
driven into bedrock under the river that supported the 300-foot
bridge.
   The temporary bridge had been in use for several months while a
new bridge was being built to replace a 94-year-old span, Brayshaw
said.
   Just as engineers were moving to barricade the bridge, a
100-foot section collapsed. Late Friday, three other bridges over
the Great Miami were closed.
</TEXT>
