<DOCNO> AP890527-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Troops     05-27 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Troops,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settling In at Camp Roadrunner</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP ROADRUNNER, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spec. 4 Mike Boyd of DeQuincy,
La. misses shrimp gumbo and having a good place to drive his 1988
Dodge Shadow Turbo _ fast.
   Pfc. Thomas McNamara of Kansas City, Mo., eats lukewarm chicken
a la king, heated in his armored personnel carrier by a long day of
sun.
   The sergeants of the ``Latin Corner'' pass the time with a game
of dominoes.
   All are from the 1st of the 61st _ 1st Battalion, 61st infantry,
5th Infantry Division, known as the Roadrunners _ moved suddenly
from Fort Polk, La. and plunked down in a jungle clearing in Panama.
   They miss their wives, their girlfriends, their children, their
freedom _ Panama City is a forbidden 10-minute drive away.
   It's hard to sleep in a bubble ``tent'' the size of a tennis
court with 169 other men, even if it has air conditioning. There's
one color television and one telephone. There's a lot of work, a
lot of heat, a lot of bugs, a lot of grousing.
   ``A lot of them don't act proud now, but once they get back and
think about what they've done, some backbustin' work, that'll
change,'' said Spec. 4 James ``Mike'' Colburn.
   Colburn has seen it before. He's 39, served in the Army from
1969 to 1972, including 11 months in Vietnam. He re-enlisted in
1987 when some factories closed back in Owensboro, Ky.
   ``This is going to give a lot of the NCOs (noncommissioned
officers) and officers something to put under their belt.
Everybody's going to learn something. We've been at it pretty good
_ reminds me of basic training, and I did that twice. It'll give
1-61 some recognition,'' Colburn said.
   The officers talk about training, about heat.
   ``We haven't had any morale problems so far,'' said Capt. John
Lyles of Wichita Falls, Texas, the assistant operations officer.
``We're trying to set up a system of day passes so people can go
fishing, golfing, picnic. Get a day away from camp.''
   The soldiers arrived May 13 when President Bush decided to move
1,900 extra troops into Panama Canal installations to augment
security because of civil unrest following May 7 elections.
   They all know who the real power is _ Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, head of the Panamanian Defense Forces, also known as
``pineapple face.''
   ``We'd chase old pineapple face in a second, if that's what they
want,'' said Sgt. Birriel, who said his first name is ``Ranger.''
   ``Relations with the Panamanians are good. The ones we meet, 80
percent are against Noriega,'' said Sgt. Feliciano Villanueva, a
combat medic.
   Villanueva, of Bayamon, P.R., and Brooklyn, is the old man of
the Latin Corner at 32, ``Papa'' to a group of eight sergeants from
Puerto Rico via New York City.
   ``We didn't bring any dominoes. They just packed us up with two
duffel bags and moved us out,'' said Sgt. Wilfredo Hernandez, of
Bayamon and the Bronx.
   Hernandez thinks he's solved the domino drought. He gave a
Panamanian woman some money to buy a set in town, where retired men
while away the hours at dominoes in the city parks.
   Some people lost more than dominoes in the move, said Boyd, who
tells of a buddy who was about to get married when the call came.
   ``He married Panama instead of the bride,'' said Boyd.
   ``I had a house closing, I left it all for my wife to do,'' said
Spec. 4 Ricky Zimmerman of Hoboken, N.J.
   Food? ``It's hamburgers in line A, chopped steak in Line B,''
joked one soldier. There were extra ribs Thursday night, but a lot
of people have to settle for MRE, or meals-ready-to-eat, like APC
driver McNamara's chicken in a blue plastic bag.
   Boyd is thinking of supplementing the diet with iguana or a
rat-like creature he saw in the jungle. ``I used to hunt a lot back
home,'' he said. ``And I've seen some big shrimp here.''
   The soldiers spend their spare time, what there is of it,
writing letters, because the telephone costs $11 to $15 for three
minutes.
   The rumor mill is churning all the time. Today the rumor is
it'll be a 45-day deployment. Yesterday, it was six months.
   When do they want to get out?
   ``It's hot, I'm ready now,'' said Boyd.
   July 4, says Zimmerman. That's when the New York Mets play the
Astros in Houston; he's a Mets fan, and Fort Polk is only three
hours away.
   July 21, says Colburn. That's his daughter Nikki Michelle's
sixth birthday.
</TEXT>
