<FIRST>u w PM-AT&amp;TTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0435 05-27 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Care Issue Blocks Settlement as Midnight Deadline Nears</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with four grafs to update with talks resuming.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T and its unions raced against the clock
today in hopes of negotiating new contracts before existing pacts
expire tonight, but a bitter dispute over medical benefits
threatened to block a settlement.
   ``There's a lot to be done and a lot of hard bargaining going
on,'' a company official said today shortly after the negotiators
returned to the bargaining table.
   It remained unclear whether the two sides could resolve their
differences over medical benefits, described by one source as ``the
major block to a settlement.'' Also up in the air was whether the
unions would immediately call a strike in the absence of a
settlement.
   After a long and frantic day of negotiating Friday, both sides
publicly continued to express hope of reaching new contracts before
existing pacts affecting about 160,000 workers expire at 11:59 p.m.
EDT. But they say such a development hinges on a major breakthrough
on the benefits package, which has dominated the talks from the
outset.
   ``If we can settle health care _ no easy task _ then we can
reach agreement on wages and the other issues,'' a union source
said late Friday. ``This is the major block to a settlement.''
   Sources close to the negotiations said progress has been made
but they cautioned that negotiations are at a fragile stage and
could turn for the worse. In an arrangement likely to be repeated
today, formal negotiating committees met Friday at a Washington
hotel while the two union presidents and AT&amp;T's top negotiator held
separate meetings periodically on the major issues.
   It remained unclear as the deadline approached whether the
unions would call a strike immediately if no agreement is reached.
Union officials have refused to disclose their plans but have
hinted strongly that they would not strike right away, particularly
if agreement on a contract appeared near.
   Instead, the unions have a number of other strategies designed
to pressure the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. into a
settlement, primarily a nationwide labor boycott of AT&amp;T
long-distance service that the unions contend could cut the
company's long-distance revenues by up to 8 percent.
   As two levels of negotiations continued late Friday, both sides
reported progress but said bitter union opposition to AT&amp;T's health
care proposal remained a substantial barrier to a settlement.
   The unions, the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, vehemently oppose
AT&amp;T's demand that workers pay more up front for medical care. The
company says it needs to reduce its $1 billion annual medical bill,
but the unions have demanded expanded benefits while promising to
devise new cost-control measures.
   Hectic negotiations Friday were marked by repeated exchanges of
proposals and counter offers, including a significant AT&amp;T offer to
limit the use of temporary workers _ a key union job-security
demand.
   The sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said AT&amp;T
proposed in an informal meeting among top officials from both sides
to revise its health care package. Neither side would discuss
details. But a union official said, ``It was a reconfiguration of
the existing offer and it is unacceptable.''
   In addition to offering to regulate use of temporary workers,
AT&amp;T has amended and expanded its contract proposal to improve eye
and dental care and its parental leave policy, company officials
said. Also, it has proposed for the first time allowing leave for
workers to care for sick relatives.
   Those proposals are in addition to the formal offer the company
made Monday, a package which provided varying base wage increases
and lump sum payments depending on job classification and also a
new profit-sharing plan for union workers.
</TEXT>
