<HEAD>Marathon Concert Held to Support Beijing Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300,000 people crowded into a 12-hour
concert held Saturday to raise money for students demonstrating for
reform in Beijing.
   The concert, billed as Hong Kong's largest and longest, began
with an explanation of the Beijing student movement, which includes
demands for democratic reforms such as press freedom. The concert
involved more than 100 musicians from Hong Kong and Taiwan, ranging
from rock stars to opera singers.
   Organizers said the concert, held at a racecourse, raised $1.55
million, which was six times more than expected.
   Television and radio stations broadcast the event live with only
commercial and news breaks. Organizers set up a huge outdoor screen
to keep the audience abreast of the latest developments in Beijing.
   Meanwhile, more than 1,000 senior citizens marched to the Xinhua
News Agency, China's de facto embassy in this British colony, which
reverts to Chinese rule in 1997.
   In separate protests, 300 youths and 100 journalists also
marched to Xinhua in support of the Beijing students, while 300
trucks slowly drove past the agency.
