<FIRST>r a AM-TeenAssault     05-27 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Assault,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Struggling To Understand Sexual Assault Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this affluent community,
shaken by the arrests of five high school students on charges of
sexually assaulting a mentally retarded girl, have raised another
disturbing question.
   Why did it take weeks for authorities to bring charges in the
case when students in the high school were buzzing about the
incident the day after it occurred? Authorities say it just took
that long to investigate, while others charge it was a sign of the
popularity and privileged status of the suspects.
   ``Everybody has known about it for a while,'' said a student who
would give her name only as W. Sanford.
   Police say that on March 1, 13 teen-agers accompanied a
17-year-old mentally retarded girl to the home of two of the teens,
where she was sexually assaulted with a broomstick and a miniature
baseball bat. No sexual intercourse took place.
   The girl, who was an acquaintance of the boys, is not capable of
understanding or consenting to what happened, authorities said.
   Five teens, all 17 or 18, were arrested Wednesday, the day after
a New York City television station broadcast a report on the
incident. Three were charged as adults with conspiracy and assault
charges, two were charged as juveniles. The other eight, who were
not charged, watched the incident but did not intervene,
investigators said.
   Patrick Pignatello, a lifelong resident, said: ``This doesn't
happen in Glen Ridge. I know those kids. I know every family in
town. These kids are well educated. They know right from wrong.
They're not on drugs or alcohol.
   ``I just can't understand how anything like this could happen.''
   Some residents are angry that the March 1 incident is being
compared to the case from New York City, 20 miles to the east, in
which a Central Park jogger was raped by a gang of teen-age boys.
   ``Because of the proximity and time of the New York `wilding'
incidents, analogies are made of rich white boys vs. poor black
youths in the city,'' said Kevin Rigby, an attorney for one of the
teen-agers charged. ``You've got two very distinct incidents here
and it's not fair to make comparisons.''
   Some students and residents say the delay in the arrests may be
due to the popularity of the students, many of whom are athletes.
They also note that among the eight who witnessed the incident but
was not charged is a township police lieutenant's son.
   Missy Sheuermann, a township resident, said she suspected a
coverup by authorities to protect a group of privileged students.
   ``It's appalling. ... No one's ever going to hear the truth,''
she said.
   Students said rumors began circulating the day after the
incident and it was known throughout the 340-student school by the
time of the arrest. ``Everybody knew about it,'' said one junior,
who said he didn't want his name used for fear of reprisals.
   Ray Weiss, spokesman for the Essex County prosecutor's office,
said the length of the investigation was justified by the factors
involved _ the mental state of the victim and the number of boys
involved.
   ``It is the normal course that a complex investigation takes,''
Weiss said. ``You do it as thoroughly as you can until you're
satisfied you've gone as far as you can.''
   The girl first reported the incident March 4 to a teacher at
West Orange High School, where she attends special education
classes.
   The delay by a victim in reporting the attack is common in
sexual abuse cases, said Dr. Jeffrey Segal, coordinator of a
Morristown Memorial Hospital program that cares for victims of
violent assaults.
   ``I think victims in general, children or adults, fear of what
would happen if they do reveal an attack,'' Segal said. ``Also
there is the fear, will people believe them?''
   Police were notified about three weeks later. Rose McCaffrey,
Glen Ridge superintendent of schools, said school officials wanted
to be sure of the nature of the incident before calling in police.
Glen Ridge school officials heard about the incident from West
Orange officials and from a student.
   ``There was certainly no cover-up on our behalf,'' McCaffrey
said. ``We cannot answer why it took them that long to investigate.
They shared no information with us.''
</TEXT>
