<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-HouseLeadership 4thLd-Writethru a0528 05-27 1078</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Leadership, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0528,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coelho Quitting Congress Rather Than Face Ethics Questions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBs for 9th graf pvs with five new grafs to update with Gephardt
planning run for leadership post; pickup 10th graf pvs: ``He has been ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony Coelho, No. 3 in the House
Democratic leadership, said today he will quit Congress rather than
endure a protracted ethics investigation similar to the one that
has driven Speaker Jim Wright to the brink of resignation.
   Coelho, the majority whip in the House, has come under fire in
recent weeks for a $100,000 junk bond investment in which he earned
more than $6,000 without investing any money, and for other
financial dealings.
   In a statement, Coelho said his ability to work in Congress and
serve the Democratic Party ``has been diminished by needless and
baseless charges about my investments or private life. I have
simply spent too much time building the party and trying to help
people to have my attention or abilities devoted to such
distractions.''
   ``Accordingly, I will not seek the office of majority leader.
Instead, I will tender my resignation as majority whip, and will
also resign my seat in Congress _ on my (47th) birthday _ June
15th,'' he said.
   The California congressman said that ``all week, my colleagues
have expressed their confidence in me and their support for a
leader's race. I would have preferred to land in that race with
both feet, and would have had the votes to win.
   ``Moreover, my attorneys remain convinced that a normal business
transaction, admittedly marred by reporting errors, posed no legal
problems for me, and I accept their advice,'' Coelho said.
   He added: ``Undoubtedly, some will think this decision was
motivated by weakness in my political standing or my legal
position. They are entitled to their opinions, but they are wrong.''
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., termed Coelho's
departure as ``a loss,'' adding: ``In the current environment,
realistically, there might be a long period of inquiry which he
feels would be damaging to the party or to the House for which he
has deep affection.''
   With Coelho out of the leadership scramble, Rep. Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., has decided to run for majority leader ``no matter
what,'' a congressional source close to Gephardt said today on
condition of anonymity.
   ``He has been persuaded to run,'' the Democratic source said
today.
   Gephardt learned of Coelho's planned resignation through news
accounts Friday night and was in his congressional office today
calling colleagues to seek their support for his leadership bid.
   According to the Gephardt source, the Missouri congressman has
decided to ``unequivocally'' abandon any presidential plans for
1992 if he wins the majority leader position. Gephardt
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic presidential nomination in
1988.
   Gephard said in a statement he was ``stunned and saddened by
Tony's decision.
   ``He has been an extraordinarily able and effective leader in
the House. He has also been my good friend, and he will continue to
be,'' Gephardt said.
   A top Democratic leadership source, who spoke only on condition
he not be named, said Coelho ``just said he couldn't be an
effective majority leader with these charges out there.''
   Coelho's decision, first disclosed in an interview published in
today's editions of The New York Times, further complicates
Democratic efforts to regroup in the wake of the furor over
Wright's ethical problems.
   Foley is expected to become speaker if Wright resigns as
expected next week.
   Earlier Friday, Coelho had been passing word that he would
attempt to move up to majority leader, but his decision to depart
leaves open the posts of majority leader, whip and possibly several
other leadership posts.
   Coelho told the Times he was taking the actions to avoid a
protracted investigation of his personal finances.
   ``I want to give my party a chance to move on,'' the Times
quoted him as saying. ``I don't intend to put my party through more
turmoil. I don't intend to put this institution through more
turmoil. And more importantly, I don't intend to put my family
through more turmoil.''
   ``If I can't be leader and if I can't be whip, it's time to try
a new and different challenge,'' he said.
   Earlier this month, Coelho acknowledged that a California
savings and loan executive set him up in a junk bond investment
that netted him a $6,882 profit without him having to put up any of
his own money.
   However, Coelho had said that except for some reporting errors
the 1986 deal was ``totally above board'' and he did nothing wrong.
   Coelho has been a rising star in the House. The Californian was
widely respected and liked by other Democrats for his work as
chairman of the party's campaign committee, which raised funds and
provided campaign services for the party's candidates.
   But some Democrats expressed concern privately over the possible
political damage to the party if Coelho took on a more prominent
role at a time when his business dealings were coming under close
scrutiny on the heels of Wright's apparently unsuccessful campaign
to fend off multiple ethics allegations.
   A report released by Coelho on May 14 showed that Thomas
Spiegel, chief executive officer of the Columbia Savings and Loan
Assn. of Beverly Hills, Calif., purchased $100,000 in bonds for
Coelho and held them until Coelho could raise money to pay for them.
   Spiegel also provided half of the money to finance the bonds.
   The bond was sold to Coelho by the executive a month later at
the initial offering price, saving Coelho about $4,000 compared to
the bond's market price at the time. The Los Angeles Times reported
this week that the Justice Department was opening a criminal
investigation of whether Coelho received favored treatment, but
Coelho said the story was wrong.
   However, Coelho acknowledged that he regretted the deal. He put
his personal funds into a blind trust last year, and he said he
wished he had done it earlier.
   According to Coelho's report, he first considered investing his
1986 campaign funds in 12{ percent bonds, based on a suggestion by
Spiegel. Coelho ruled out that type of investment for his campaign,
but Spiegel suggested the congressman himself could make an
investment in the bonds.
   In the report earlier this month, Coelho's lawyer, Robert F.
Bauer, concluded that Spiegel's role in the transaction could not
be considered a ``gift'' which would violate House rules, because
Coelho paid him interest.
</TEXT>
