<FIRST>r a AM-People     05-27 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Redford first fell in love with
Yosemite when he was 10 years old and his mother took him to the
park as a reward for recovering from a slight case of polio, the
actor and outdoorsman said.
   ``I was quite sick,'' Redford said in a telephone interview
Friday. ``I grew up in a poor neighborhood in Los Angeles and never
had an opportunity to get into the outdoors.''
   Redford, who is narrating a documentary about the park called,
``Yosemite: The Fate of Heaven,'' said he and his mother drove
about eight hours through the redwoods and into a tunnel entering
Yosemite National Park.
   ``We came out the other end, and what I saw absolutely put me
away,'' he said.
   Rising above him in the 760,000-acre park were El Capitan,
Cathedral Rocks and Half Dome, with Yosemite Falls plunging 2,000
feet down sheer granite cliffs.
   ``Everything emanates from that moment, my environmental work,
my love for the outdoors,'' Redford said.
   The one-hour documentary examines the difficulty of preserving
Yosemite, while opening the park to more than 3 million visitors
each year. Yosemite is located about 200 miles southeast of San
Francisco. The park celebrates its 100th anniversary next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Best-selling author Jeffrey Archer said Saturday
the Soviet Union had offered ``real money'' for a Western book for
the first time _ paying him $10,000 for his 1982 saga ``Kane and
Abel.''
   Archer said a similar Soviet deal had been arranged for John Le
Carre's spy novel, ``The Russia House.''
   ``Up to now the Russians either `stole' your books or offered
you rubles which you had to go to Russia to be able to spend,''
Archer said.
   ``But now, in this latest example of glasnost, (Soviet leader
Mikhail) Gorbachev has said that Russian publishers have to pay
proper prices if they want to be competitive,'' he said.
   Archer claime both books were anti-Russian ``in the sense that
Le Carre's is about a spy in Russia and mine is about a man who
escapes from Russia and makes good in the United States.''
   ``So they have had the courage not simply to pick books which
automatically say what a wonderful country the Soviet Union is,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ``Six Million Dollar Man'' Lee Majors
has been awarded more than $500,000 in a lawsuit filed against a
former business partner in two oil rig drilling companies.
   A Garfield County district court awarded Majors and partner Ray
Davis of Enid about $1 million after deliberating more than five
hours Friday.
   The men had sued Vaughn and Laura Good for $4.9 million for
allegedly spending company money to pay personal bills, and buy oil
equipment and invest in oil wells and then keep the profits for
themselves.
   Majors testified during the two-week trial that he invested $3.2
million in two oil drilling rig companies with the Goods and lost
more than $1 million. Davis claimed he lost more than $1.5 million.
   Attorneys for the defendants said, however, that Majors, who
starred in television's ``The Six Million Dollar Man'' and ``The
Big Valley,'' and Davis may not receive their complete awards
because the judge in the case agreed to impose a $90,000 cap on
judgments against Laura Good and Vaughn Good has filed for
bankruptcy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has joined the
select and historic band of Freemen of the City of London, but
there were doubts she would exercise one of her new rights _
driving sheep unhindered across London Bridge.
   In a glittering and ancient ceremony Friday at Guildhall, seat
of the square-mile City of London, which is now the capital's
financial district, Mrs. Thatcher joined a list of national and
international notables.
   In his welcoming address, Lord Mayor Sir Christopher Collett
noted that her right as a Freeman to drive sheep across London
Bridge had fallen out of favor in recent years.
   But Mrs. Thatcher's new status does mean she can request an
audience of Queen Elizabeth II and present her with a petition
pleading for help.
   As part of the ceremony, Mrs. Thatcher affirmed an oath of
allegiance to the queen and promised to hinder and give warning of
any plots against her.
   The prime minister, flanked by Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie and members of her Cabinet, also promised never to be
``idle'' and work constantly for her own advantage and the
advantage of others.
   The Freedom of the City of London dates from 1275. Before the
19th century, being a Freeman was essential for anyone wanting to
trade or be a craftsman in the City of London, and Freemen were
exempted from paying tolls at markets and fairs and from being
drafted into the armed forces.
</TEXT>
