<HEAD>2,200 Workers Protest Company Financial Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,200 workers from central
Yugoslavia on Saturday protested the government's closing of a
food-processing company implicated in the country's largest
financial scandal.
   The company's workers arrived from the town of Velika Kladusa on
Friday and gathered in a sports stadium in the capital. They
demanded authorities allow the bankrupt Agrokomerc company to
resume production.
   They also asked that a former company manager, now on trial in
Bosnia-Hrrcegovina, be released from detention and that details of
the reported fraud be made public. The company reportedly issued
some $1 billion in uncovered promissory notes before being closed.
   The protesters said they will rally before the federal
parliament on Monday if their demands are not met, the Tanjug news
agency reported.
