<SECOND>AM-Flag Flap, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Party's Colors Cause Hue And Cry</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 6th graf, `Herbert Castilli...' to CORRECT spelling of
Castillo. Pickup 7th, `The new...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party are seeing red _ and white and green.
   Party leaders are upset that the upstart Democratic
Revolutionary Party has adopted the same three colors used for 60
years by the governing party on its flags and emblems.
   Red, white and green also happen to be Mexico's national colors.
   Governing party leader Fernando Ortiz Arana said during a
meeting of the Federal Electoral Commission on Friday that the
party's newly formed rival should be given 30 days to switch
colors, according to the Excelsior news service.
   But Democratic Revolutionary Party leaders say the governing
party should not have a monopoly on the three colors Mexicans
associate with patriotism.
   Herbert Castillo, a party leader and former presidential
candidate of the Mexican Socialist Party, said his former party had
been allowed to use the colors red and green. The socialist party
is being absorbed by the Democratic Revolutionary Party.
   ``We just want to add white now,'' Castillo said.
   The new party is being formed by Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a former
governor of Michoacan state who came in second to governing party
candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari in the July 1988 elections.
Salinas took office in December.
   The Electoral Commission, which is dominated by the governing
party, currently is holding hearings on the formation of the new
party.
</TEXT>
