<FIRST>r i AM-AncientTomb     05-27 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ancient Tomb,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold-Stuffed Tomb Unearthed at Nimrud in Northern Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists have unearthed the
gold-stuffed tomb of two women in what appears to be the richest
discovery ever made at ancient Nimrud in northern Iraq.
   The 2,700-year-old tomb in the palace of King Ashurnasirpal II
contained more than 55 pounds of gold jewelery including diadems,
necklaces, earrings, belts and anklets, the English-language
Baghdad Observer reported Friday.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Cyprus, carried
details of the newspaper report.
   Nimrud, a sprawling site 250 miles north of Baghdad, was a major
city of the Assyrian empire that extended from the Persian Gulf to
the Mediterranean in the first millennium B.C.
   Ashurnasirpal II was a ruthless but brilliant military leader
who built the vast palace at Nimrud in the 9th century B.C.
   Scores of Iraqi and foreign archaeological teams have dug at
Nimrud in a century-and-a-half of excavations since British
explorer Henry Layard uncovered huge stone sculptures and
inscriptions there in the 1840s.
   The explorers included British archaeologist Max Mallowan, the
husband of author Agatha Christie, who excavated close to the newly
found tomb between 1949 and 1958.
   Some of Layard's and Mallowan's finds are displayed in the
British Museum in London, as well as in Iraq's national museum in
Baghdad.
   Muzahem Mahmoud, the Iraqi archaeologist who made the new
discovery, said an inscribed stone tablet found in the
32-by-14-foot burial chamber identified one of the women as Yabaya
of the Assyrian royal court, the newspaper reported.
   The inscription in wedge-shaped cuneiform script also placed a
curse on anyone who opened the tomb.
   ``If anyone lays his hands on my tomb, or opens my grave, or
steals my jewelery, I pray to the gods of the nether world that his
soul shall roam in the scorching sun after death...Let the ghost of
insomnia take hold of him for ever and ever,'' it said.
   The other woman was identified only as a much younger person
named Taliya, the newspaper said.
   Yabaya's possessions included gold needles, a bronze mirror with
its enamel handle encrusted with precious stones, and tiny tongs
for applying kohl, a dark eye makeup, the paper said.
   ``We found more than 100 earrings beside her skull, some small,
some large. She had all her personal belongings buried with her in
the grave,'' Mahmoud said.
   The report said that rich royal tombs had been unearthed at
Ashur, another Assyrian city, but none contained as many precious
objects as the Nimrud grave.
   It said that although the Assyrian empire is well-documented,
there are few references to the role of women at the royal court.
   However, Queen Semiramis is known to have ruled Assyria for five
years at the end of the 9th century B.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Bush 5thLd-Writethru a0530 05-27 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0530,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Says Allies Must Be Consulted About U.S. Troop Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs old graf 5, bgng ``Before an, with new grafs 5-7 to UPDATE
with Bush-Pope meeting; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng ``Fitzwater refused.
Will stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As President Bush held presummit talks with Italian
leaders, the White House said today the United States will not
withdraw troops from Europe without consulting its Western allies.
There also were hints the United States might ease economic
sanctions against the Soviet Union.
   Leaving the door open for troop reductions, White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the latest Soviet proposal for
reducing tanks and other conventional forces in Europe presents
``some opportunities'' for the West.
   Fitzwater said Bush will discuss conventional force levels with
15 other allied leaders when a NATO summit meeting begins in
Brussels on Monday.
   On three separate occasions today, Bush brushed aside reporters'
questions about whether he was planning to announce withdrawal of
as many as 30,000 troops from Europe, nearly 10 percent of the
total stationed there.
   Bush held private talks with Pope John Paul II at the Vatican
Saturday evening. Afterwards the pontiff praised Bush for
combatting ``the moral crisis'' of drugs.
   Bush in turn spoke warmly of the pope's efforts for world peace
and said ``we've made progress in reducing armaments.''
   Before the audience with the pope, Bush held talks at a 16th
century hillside villa with Italian Premier Ciriaco De Mita, and
later conferred over lunch at the Quirinale Palace with President
Francesco Cossiga.
   Fitzwater refused to discuss possible troop cutbacks but said,
``The United States will not unilaterally withdraw troops from
Europe,'' meaning that Bush would consult first with its allies.
   In Brussels, said Fitzwater, ``the president clearly will be
discussing a number of ideas _ many of them have not been presented
before.'' He said he could not discuss details.
   Asked whether Bush might be willing to ease economic sanctions
that were imposed against the Soviets in 1980, Fitzwater pointedly
noted that the Soviet Union has withdrawn its troops from
Afghanistan.
   It was the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in December 1979 that
prompted the United States to impose a ban on technology transfers
to Moscow.
   Fitzwater said any action on lifting sanctions would depend on
talks with U.S. allies. ``This is a matter we would have to
discuss,'' he said.
   Fitzwater left the door open for possible U.S.-Soviet talks on
reducing American troop levels in Europe. Until now, the United
States has been willing to talk only about NATO and Warsaw Pact
tanks, artillery and other equipment but has ruled out direct
negotiations over troop levels.
   Fitzwater said the Soviets were ``coming around to NATO
thinking'' and that there was ``a different climate we find
promising.''
   The Washington Times reported that Bush planned to propose a 10
percent cutback in American troop strength in Europe, which totals
between 305,000 and 325,000 personnel.
   The Washington Post quoted sources in today's editions as saying
the administration is considering an offer to negotiate cuts in
troop strength, aircraft and helicopters in Europe if the Soviet
Union agrees to cuts in tanks, armored personnel carriers and
artillery pieces.
   Bush has been under intense pressure at home and abroad to reply
to a series of disarmament proposals from Moscow with some ideas of
his own. White House officials readily acknowledge that Bush has
seemed too negative while Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
been portrayed as a peacemaker.
   There is pressure in Congress for withdrawal of at least 8,000
troops, to pull back Americans whose jobs are eliminated by the
1987 U.S.-Soviet treaty to destroy medium-range nuclear missiles.
   Fitzwater said discussions about conventional arms _ troops,
tanks and non-nuclear artillery _ would be ``a major thrust of the
discussions'' when Bush attends a NATO summit Monday and Tuesday
with leaders of 15 other Western nations.
   ``Any ideas in this area would be ones the president would want
to discuss with the allies,'' Fitzwater said. ``He would raise
(them) with his partners at this session before he discusses
anything publicly.''
   The NATO meeting has been clouded by West German demands for
Washington and Moscow to begin negotiations soon to reduce _
possibly eliminate _ short-range nuclear missiles in central Europe.
   The United States and Britain oppose such talks now because of
the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact's superiority in tanks, troops and other
conventional weapons. Washington and London also fear the
negotiations would ignite public pressure to eliminate the missiles
entirely.
   Fitzwater said Bush and the Italian premier agreed on the need
to encourage reforms in the Soviet Union and maintain NATO unity.
They also discussed East-West talks in Vienna on reducing
conventional forces in Europe.
   On his arrival shortly before midnight Friday, Bush made no
reference to reports of possible troop withdrawals.
   Instead, he declared the United States wants a ``stronger and
more united Europe,'' and said he plans to be ``actively engaged in
Eastern Europe, promoting measures to encourage political and
economic liberalization in Poland.''
   Bush plans to visit Poland in July.
</TEXT>
