<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceCatalog     05-27 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Catalog,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Space Command Logs 20,000th Space Object</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmos 2021 became Object No.
20,000 in the U.S. Space Command's space catalog this week.
   The Soviet satellite was logged into the catalog at 5:30 a.m.
Wednesday, the time of its launch.
   The Space Command's Surveillance Center is tracking about 7,000
manufactured space objects, but has cataloged every satellite or
piece of junk larger than a softball in Earth orbit since Sputnik
was launched on Oct. 4, 1957.
   The center has tracked a wrench and camera dropped by
astronauts, bits and pieces of exploded rocket bodies, satellites
and shuttles.
   Most of the 13,000 objects that have fallen back toward Earth
burned up in the atmosphere.
   But a few more notable objects, such as the U.S.-built Skylab
and the Soviet-built Cosmos 954, were too large to burn up and came
crashing back to Earth. Cosmos 954 and its nuclear reactor fell in
northern Canada in January 1978; Skylab fell in Australia and the
Indian Ocean in July 1979.
   The Space Surveillance Center uses radar and optical tracking
devices to keep track of the objects.
   The information is used to ensure that the shuttle or other
rockets depositing payloads in space don't run into objects in
orbit, or that a falling satellite isn't mistaken for a missile
attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet 6thLd-Writethru   05-27 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet, 6th Ld-Writethru,a0509,0857</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reformers Defeated in Bid for Supreme Soviet Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 18th pvs, `The Muscovites...' to CORRECT that Borovik won
majority but finished behind those who won seats. Pickup 19th, ``Yeltsin
lost...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist maverick Boris N. Yeltsin and other
outspoken Moscow reformers lost their bids today for seats on a new
standing legislature, and one suggested they join forces to fight
the Communist Party.
   Yeltsin and other reformers were elected in March to the
2,250-member Congress of People's Deputies, which in turn today
chose the smaller, full-time Supreme Soviet and in doing so shut
out many progressive candidates.
   Many party chiefs and top bureaucrats also faced stiff
opposition from fellow congressmen but were elected to the Supreme
Soviet, the revamped law-making body that replaces the rubber-stamp
predecessor of the same name.
   The deputies voted Friday night from a ballot of 600 candidates
_ all members of the congress _ to fill the 542-member Supreme
Soviet.
   In the Baltic delegations, another hotbed of reform, deputies
nominated only as many candidates as they had seats and succeeded
in electing a number of radical leaders to the Supreme Soviet.
   Yeltsin won a majority of the votes of his fellow deputies but
ran last out of 12 candidates vying for 11 Supreme Soviet seats
designated for the Russian federation. Deputy Yuri A. Osipyan,
chairman of the commission that counted the ballots overnight, said
Yeltsin got 1,185 votes in the Congress of People's Deputies, with
964 members of the national congress voting against him.
   Yeltsin said he was saddened and upset by the results but
pledged to continue his crusade, indicating he might seek the vice
presidency, which also will be voted on by the congress.
   ``I must fight to the end,'' he told reporters. He added that
was his responsibility to the millions of Muscovites who sent him
to the Congress. ``I must fulfill their will and their orders. I
wouldn't throw away any job.''
   The anti-establishment Yeltsin headed a list of vanquished
Moscow-based reformers and radicals, including sociologist Tatyana
Zaslavskaya; economist Gavril Popov; Ilya Zaslavsky, an advocate
for the handicapped; historian Sergei Stankevich; and biologist
Alexei Yablokov.
   In a nationally televised session held in the Kremlim Palace of
Congresses, many deputies applauded in delight as Osipyan announced
the radicals' defeat.
   Before the balloting, some deputies complained the nominating
procedure had been rigged to keep party and government officials in
power.
   ``We have formed a Brezhnev-Stalin Supreme Soviet,'' said
progressive historian Yuri Afanasyev in dismay as election results
were announced for the new 542-seat legislature. He called the
results depressing.
   Popov declared ``the apparatus has undoubtedly won'' and called
on progressive deputies from throughout the country to form an
``independent deputies' group'' to fight Communist Party and state
bureaucrats.
   ``The apparatus clearly wants to get retaliation, clearly wants
to impose its own way at the Congress,'' Popov charged. He said
``deputies of a democratic orientation'' sought at first to work
with fellow parliamentarians, but that ``from the beginning, our
work has met with disbelief and prejudice.''
   In consequence, ``a group of deputies considers it necessary to
withdraw from the Moscow delegation,'' the economist announced.
``We are going to form ... an independent deputies' group, and
invite all deputies to join us.''
   If reformers unite, it would be the first opposition faction in
the congress, where for decades the Kremlin leadership has imposed
its will unimpeded by opposition.
   The deputies elected some more mainstream figures who proclaim
support for Gorbachev's program of ``perestroika,'' or
restructuring, but who refrained at the congress from fiery
rhetoric. They included agriculture reform advocate Alexei
Emelyanov, Izvestia editor Ivan Laptev, Soviet Academy of Sciences
vice president Yevgeny Velikhov and independent historian Roy
Medvedev.
   The Muscovites put up 55 candidates for the 29 seats allotted
them, defending the principle of multicandidate elections but
ensuring some of their number would be defeated. Many old-style
candidates, including former cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, beat
out the reformers.
   Yeltsin lost his job as Moscow party boss in November 1987 after
he criticized the slow pace of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms and suggested it was time for a multiparty system to end
the communists' legal monopoly on power.
   In his congressional campaign he attacked official privilege and
called for a better life for average Soviets, and won nearly 90
percent of the vote.
   Yeltsin and the other deputies from Moscow drafted their own
congressional agenda, including radical measures to revive the
shortage-ridden Soviet economy. But the congress rejected any move
to alter the agenda.
   In the Supreme Soviet vote, Vitaly I. Vorotnikov, the only
member of the ruling Communist Party Politburo to stand as a
candidate, met with stiff opposition, with 761 deputies voting
against him. His 1,388 votes, however, were enough for him to
outpoll Yeltsin and be elected.
   Valentin Falin, head of the party's policy-making Central
Committee's International Department, was opposed by 373 deputies,
and Alexander Kapto, chief of the party's Ideological Department,
got 282 ``no'' votes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
