<DOCNO> AP890527-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i GreekPrimeMinister Companion FirsttoArriveatNATOSummit
05-27 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>Greek Prime Minister, Companion, First to Arrive at NATO Summit</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By PHILIPPE NEURAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Prime Minister Andreas
Papandreou, accompanied by mistress Dimitra Liani, was first to
arrive here Saturday to attend the 40th anniversary NATO summit.
   His estranged wife, American-born Margaret Papandreou, was due
in Sunday to take part in a peace meeting coinciding with the
summit of leaders of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. The gathering begins Monday.
   Marching through an honor guard of Belgian military policemen,
Papandreou was welcomed at Brussels National Airport by Christos
Zacharakis, the Greek ambassador to NATO, and other diplomats.
   One step behind was Miss Liani, the 35-year-old former air
stewardess who lives with the Greek premier and accompanies him
everywhere.
   She was dressed in a long, multi-colored flowered jacket, a
royal blue blouse, a wide black belt and a short purple skirt that
matched the color of her lipstick and high heel shoes. A bracelet
adorned her left ankle.
   Papandreou shook hands with the Greek diplomats. So did Miss
Liani.
   The meeting was short. The prime minister did not speak with
Greek reporters and left in an embassy limousine with Miss Liani.
   Mrs. Papandreou will be attending the ``NATO Summit Watch''
meeting, a kind of ``off-summit'' of peace organizations.
   She is the international president of the ``Women for a
Meaningful Summit'' organization, a peace group set up for the
first summit between Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev and then-U.S.
President Ronald Reagan.
   Mrs. Papandreou will arrive in Brussels on Sunday and speak at
the opening session of the Summit Watch. Other speakers include:
Ralph Earle II, a former director of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency; John Isaacs, legislative director for the U.S.
organization ``Council for a Livable World,'' and former British
Air Vice-Marshal Anthony Mason.
   It does not seem likely that Mrs. Papandreou will cross paths
with her husband and his girlfriend.
   Elfie Woerner, wife of NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner,
has planned a program for spouses accompanying the NATO leaders,
including a visit to the Museum of Modern Art and a dinner.
   There was no word on Miss Liani's agenda.
   Papandreou, 70, who recently underwent heart surgery, has filed
for divorce from his wife and a ruling is expected shortly before
national elections on June 18.
   According to Athens newspaper reports, Papandreou will marry
Miss Liani in a religious ceremony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
