<DOCNO> AP890527-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     05-27 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Activist Released From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Armenian activist who was jailed late last year
after widespread unrest in the southern Caucasus region has been
released at the urging of a Communist Party leader, journalists and
activists said Saturday.
   The release of Khachik Stamboltsian, head of an Armenian charity
group, fueled speculation that Moscow may soon free 13 other
leaders of the Armenian protest movement that has been at the
center of the unrest.
   A journalist at Armenpress, the local news agency, said
Stamboltsian's return to Yerevan, the Armenian capital, led to the
cancellation of scattered strikes called to protest the detention
of the activists.
   The journalist, who requested anonymity, said in a telephone
inteview that Stamboltsian was freed after Armenian party chief
Suren Arutyunyan asked the national prosecutor to ``show humanity''
toward the detained activist.
   ``The first response was Khachik's release,'' said Yerevan
activist Hovik Vassilian. ``And now there are rumors that either
all the rest are out, or they soon will be,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   Authorities had been holding at least 14 people, 11 of them
members of the Karabakh Committee that spearheaded demonstrations
and strikes in a jurisdictional dispute touched off by ethnic
friction.
   The Karabakh Committee last year launched a campaign for Armenia
to annex the Nagorno-Karabakh region, where three-quarters of the
162,000 inhabitants are ethnic Armenians. Nagorno-Karabakh is part
of the republic of Azerbaijan.
   The Kremlin rejected the unification demand, putting
Nagorno-Karabakh under Moscow's direct control instead and jailing
the committee members.
   The Armenian drive to annex Nagorno-Karabakh, launched in
February 1988, led to ethnic strife between predominantly Christian
Armenians and mostly Moslem Azerbaijanis in which more than 90
people were killed last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
