<DOCNO> AP890527-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BarbaraBush 1stLd-Writhethru a0547 05-27 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush, 1st Ld-Writhethru, a0547,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Dishes Out Pasta for Homeless at Vatican</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: subs 3rd graf pvs, Mrs. Bush, to update with meeting held with
Pope; picks up 4th graf pvs, At the</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush dished out pasta for homeless women at
a Vatican shelter Saturday and said she found ``great warmth and
affection'' at the facility.
   The first lady set out on her own as President Bush conferred
with Italian officials during the first leg of a four-nation
European trip. Mrs. Bush also inspected one of Rome's crumbling
monuments.
   Mrs. Bush joined her husband later in the day for an audience
with Pope John Paul II.
   At the shelter, Mrs. Bush was welcomed by resident Adelina
Lunati, 65, who presented her with a bouquet of flowers.
   ``We checked it out from head to toe,'' Mrs. Bush said of the
72-bed facility, which was opened last year by the pope and is
operated by the Missionaries of Charity, the order founded by Nobel
Peace Prize winner Mother Teresa of Calcutta.
   ``I'm going to visit Mother Teresa centers when I get back
home,'' she said.
   Mrs. Bush said she found ``great warmth and affection'' at the
shelter.
   Reporters weren't allowed to accompany Mrs. Bush as she toured
the shelter, but a Vatican official said the first lady helped
serve rigatoni al sugo _ short, hollow, tube-shaped pasta with
tomato sauce. The pasta was blessed by Australian Archbishop Edward
Cassidy, deputy Vatican secretary of state.
   Vatican spokeswoman Marjorie Weeke said Cassidy also blessed the
president and Mrs. Bush and the ``important mission they are
undertaking for the good of the U.S. and the world.''
   Afterward, Mrs. Bush inspected Arch of Constantine at the edge
of the ancient Roman Forum, where American tourists greeted her
with a chorus of ``Hello Barbara.''
   Mrs. Bush shaded her eyes from the noon sun as she looked up at
the triumphant arch erected in 315 A.D. to honor Emperor
Constantine. The superintendent of Rome's archaeology department,
Adriano La Regina explained how the arch was decorated with
fragments of other monuments.
   The state spent $1.5 million to clean off some of the black
crust caused by automobile pollution in traffic-choked Rome.
Restoration had to be halted when funds ran out, however, and the
upper half remains whiter than the bottom.
   Security was tight. Italian police, armed with automatic
weapons, were deployed along the edge of the Palatine Hill
overlooking the arch. Helicopters buzzed overhead.
   Asked by a reporter to comment on criticism that her husband has
been too cautious in dealing with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev,
Mrs. Bush said, ``Now what has that to do with ruins?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Gephardt-Leadership     05-27 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gephardt-Leadership,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gephardt Jumps Into Race for House Majority Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Missouri's Richard Gephardt began campaigning
for House majority leader Saturday, one day after Democratic Whip
Tony Coelho of California dropped plans to run and said he would
resign his seat in Congress, congressional sources said.
   Gephardt's bid for the No.2 spot in the leadership marked the
latest development in an increasingly complex scramble among
Democrats set off by the expected resignation of House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
   Gephardt was an unsuccessful candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination a year ago. His race for majority leader
means he will ``unequivocally'' abandon any plans for a White House
bid in 1992, said a source close to the Missouri lawmaker.
   The Missourian has an unblemished record on ethical matters, a
major plus in the wake of financial controversies that have caused
Coelho to resign and brought Wright to the brink of leaving the
speaker's chair.
   The seven-term St. Louis lawmaker had been lobbied hard last
week by some Democrats to run for majority leader, but he chose not
to challenge Coelho, a friend and political ally.
   ``With Tony getting out and people persuading him to run for it,
he made the decision that he would run for majority leader,'' a
Democratic congressional source said.
   Majority Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash., is expected to become
speaker if Wright resigns next week. With Coelho out of the line of
succession, the field is open for the No. 2 and No. 3 leadership
posts.
   On Saturday, Gephardt was in his Capitol Hill office calling
colleagues to seek their support for his leadership bid. His
supporters said he would be the front-runner even if challenged by
others.
   ``If Gephardt gets into it, my feeling is he is the next
majority leader,'' said Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., who had not
talked with Gephardt about the race.
   Gephardt's decision did not daunt at least one other lawmaker
who already is running for majority leader. Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga.,
who began campaigning last week, said Saturday he remains in the
race.
   It ws unclear whether Gephardt's candidacy would dissuade others
from entering the race for majority leader.
   Jenkins and Gephardt serve on the tax-writing House Ways and
Means Committee.
   Gephardt's partisans say he would provide Democrats with a
youthful, high-profile leader who could burnish the party image in
the wake of Wright's ethical problems. The 48-year-old congressman
is viewed by supporters as ``squeaky clean,'' having survived media
scrutiny in 1988.
   He also has earned a reputation as an effective television-age
advocate of tax overhaul and a get-tough trade policy, which was
the centerpiece of his presidential campaign.
   Until the disclosure that Coelho was stepping down from the
House, Gephardt was considering a run for the No.3 post of whip.
   Coelho was a key early supporter of Gephardt's unsuccessful 1988
bid for the Democratic presidential nomination, and the Missouri
lawmaker reportedly did not want to damage his friendship with
Coelho.
   But that changed Friday night when Gephardt learned of Coelho's
resignation from news accounts. Gephardt had met earlier Friday
with Coelho and was stunned when he found out later that his friend
was leaving Congress, according to a congressional source with
close ties to Gephardt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
