<DOCNO> AP890527-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BridgeCollapse Bjt   05-27 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Collapse, Bjt,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Waters Prevent Recovery Efforts at Collapsed Bridge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS2, LaserGraphic NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Powerful currents that collapsed and swallowed
a temporary one-lane bridge over the Great Miami River prevented
authorities from finding any victims or their vehicles on Saturday.
   The American Red Cross said seven people remained unaccounted
for, but there was no way to know how many of them might have been
on the bridge when it fell into the river Friday evening.
Authorities said efforts to find them could be thwarted for at
least several days by the rushing, muddy water.
   Officials are uncertain how many vehicles plunged into the river
when a 100-foot section of the bridge collapsed. Eyewitness
accounts differed, but authorities believed at least two vehicles
were on the bridge section when it gave out. The number of
passengers aboard was unclear.
   ``We still have no idea,'' said Capt. Arthur Reid of the
Hamilton County Sheriff's Department.
   The river, a tributary of the Ohio River, jumped its banks
Friday following heavy overnight rains that took two lives
elsewhere in Ohio and caused hundreds of thousands of dollars of
damage in Illinois.
   County engineers said the bridge was ordered closed a few
minutes before the collapse because of the danger from debris
pinned against it, but the order had not been carried out when the
bridge collapsed.
   The river was searched Saturday by helicopter, but no trace of
vehicles or victims was found. Authorities tried to use an
air-supported boat, but without success.
   The river crested early Saturday at about 24 feet, eight feet
over flood stage.
   ``Now it's just a matter of time before it starts receding,''
Reid said.
   The fast-flowing river, littered with trees, tires and other
debris, left searchers virtually helpless. Reid said recovery
efforts will be stalled until the waters subside.
   ``You can't even put divers out _ it's too dangerous,'' Reid
said. ``Our boats can't handle the swift currents.''
   The bridge collapsed at Miamitown, a town of 700 people about
seven miles from Cincinnati on the western side of Hamilton County.
Dozens of people gathered at the ends of the bridge Saturday,
craning their necks to see the missing section.
   Chaplains from the sheriff's department were at the scene in
case counseling was needed, but the Rev. Bruno Kremp said there
wasn't much for them to do because of the lingering uncertainty
over the victims' identities.
   The one-lane temporary bridge has been in use for only a few
months. It was erected last year to keep traffic flowing while a
94-year-old bridge is torn down and rebuilt a few feet to the
south. Traffic lights at either end of the 300-foot temporary
bridge regulated traffic over the narrow span.
   The county's chief engineer, William Brayshaw, said he ordered
the bridge closed Friday immediately after the bridge contractor,
National Engineering Co. of Strongsville, Ohio, told him that the
debris-choked river posed a danger to the span. The collapse
occurred before workers could reach it and set up barricades.
   ``The car in front of us just dropped straight down,'' said
Sharon Boebinger, who was waiting to cross the bridge when it
collapsed. ``I said, `Oh my God.' I put it in reverse and backed
up. I didn't feel the bridge shake at all. It just happened in an
instant.''
   Floods caused by heavy thunderstorms elsewhere in Ohio were
blamed for the deaths of a 20-month-old boy who drowned after
falling into a swollen creek near his grandmother's home and a
24-year-old Fostoria woman whose car was washed into a river.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseLeadership Bjt   05-27 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Leadership, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coelho Steps Down In Major Democratic Shakeup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony Coelho, the No. 3 Democrat in the
House, said Saturday he will resign from Congress to spare himself
and his party the ordeal of a protracted ethics investigation like
the one that torched the career of Speaker Jim Wright.
   The surprise announcement means House Democrats could be
installing a totally revamped leadership team by the end of next
week, with Thomas S. Foley of Washington the likely new speaker and
several candidates vying for the next two posts of majority leader
and majority whip.
   The end appeared near to Wright's 2{-year reign as speaker _ and
perhaps his 34{-year career in the House _ because of charges
brought by the House ethics committee.
   The Texas Democrat stands accused of arranging bulk sales of his
book as a way to evade House limits on outside income and of taking
gifts from a developer friend with an interest in legislation.
   Wright's lawyers failed last week in an attempt to convince the
House ethics committee to drop at least some of the charges in
exchange for the speaker's resignation. He was in seclusion this
weekend, and the House leadership was preparing for him to deliver
a resignation speech Wednesday.
   Coelho, the current whip, began running for the post of majority
leader last week when it became known that Wright was thinking
about quitting.
   However, Coelho was coming under increasing scrutiny because of
his business dealings, including a deal where a California
savings-and-loan official arranged and helped finance a junk bond
investment.
   A newspaper reported that a federal investigation had begun, and
on Friday Common Cause, the group that lobbies for stricter
government ethics, called on the House ethics committee to
investigate Coelho's finances.
   ``I have simply spent too much time building the party and
trying to help people to have my attention or abilities devoted to
such distractions,'' Coelho said in a resignation statement that
called the charges ``needless and baseless.''
   Coelho said his colleagues had expressed confidence in him and
he would have won the majority leader's race.
   ``Undoubtedly, some will think this decision was motivated by
weakness in my political standing or my legal position. They are
entitled to their opinion, but they are wrong,'' he said.
   Coelho's statement, made available to news organizations, made
no mention of it, but several legislators said privately that he
had been admonished by others not to run for higher leadership. He
would become more of a target, and further injure the party
structure, already reeling because of Wright's travails, they said.
   Coelho, himself, remained out of public view on Saturday. His
statement said the resignation is effective June 15 _ his 47th
birthday.
   Even before Coelho dropped out, Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri was being urged to challenge for the majority leader's
post. With his friend Coelho out of the race, Gephardt began his
campaign in earnest on Saturday.
   Gephardt said he was ``stunned'' by Coelho's decision and
praised the California congressman as ``an extraordinarily able and
effective leader.''
   Gephardt gave up a job in the Democratic leadership to run for
president in 1988. He is now promising colleagues he will not run
for president in 1992 if he wins the majority leader's job.
   Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., began campaigning for leader last week
as an alternative to Coelho and said Saturday he was still in the
running.
   Jenkins declined to handicap his race against Gephardt, but said
many members saw ``a need to bring some new blood, maybe outside
the (established) leadership group, into the game for the good of
the party and of the institution.''
   Jenkins has support from Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., the
powerful chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
   At least a three-way race was under way for the whip's post,
between Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., who holds Coelho's former post as
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee; Rep.
David Bonior, D-Mich., the chief deputy whip, and William H. Gray
III, D-Pa., chairman of the House Democratic Caucus.
   The election for speaker would be held immediately if Wright
were to leave because the House cannot function with that
constitutionally-mandated job vacant. The other party positions
could be elected at the same time or at a later date. But the
Democrats were expected to get it all taken care of in no more than
a week or two.
   Anthony said the resignations and the ensuing shakeup will make
the party look bad. ``In the near term, we've got a problem of
public perception,'' he said.
   But he said ``the spotlight shifts to the Republicans'' soon
because one of their leaders, Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., is the
subject of a complaint before the ethics committee.
   On the other hand, the House GOP, which has largely sat on the
sidelines during Wright's travails lest the ethics probe be seen as
a partisan vendetta, may become more aggressive.
   Republicans are likely to redouble their emphasis on
institutional changes, including pressing for campaign reform and
tougher ethics standards. That would enable them to keep political
pressure on the Democrats by keeping the ethics issue alive without
appearing to be attacking individual personalities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
