<FIRST>u i AM-US-SouthAfrica     05-27 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Leader Meets Baker, Pledges Progress for Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African Foreign Minister Roelof Botha met with
Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Saturday and pledged anew
to end white domination of blacks in his country.
   Baker and Botha also discussed a planned visit to Washington by
F.W. DeKlerk, the leader of South Africa's governing National Party
and the man expected to become the country's president later this
year.
   Baker, in a brief exchange with reporters after the meeting,
ssid Botha had ``indicated to us it is the intention of the South
African government to abolish the system of apartheid and we were
pleased to hear that.''
   Botha concurred. ``We are in the process of reform, and we are
dismantling apartheid, and we accept that white domination must
end,'' Both said.
   He said the decision was taken by the South African government
for its own policy reasons and not in response to outside pressures.
   ``It's going to be done in consultation with black leaders,''
Botha said.
   Later, the White House issued a statement saying Botha had told
Baker his party would campaign for the South African presidency
with the view that ``the days of white domination are over.''
   The statement said Baker raised questions about denial of human
and civil rights of black South Africans, individual cases of
detention and restrictions on freedom of travel.
   ``The secretary said that the U.S. government intended to engage
with a full range of black and white South Africans in an effort to
work towards the goal of producing peaceful abolition of
apartheid,'' the statement added.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that in view of the
government changes coming up in South Africa, Baker had taken
``this opportunity to explore any possible changes that might be
taking place in the policies of that government at this time.''
   The invitation to De Klerk, who would be the first top South
African leader to visit Washington in 30 years, and a meeting Bush
had earlier this month with anti-apartheid leaders, are part of a
U.S. initiative to increase contacts with South Africa.
   The United States also appears to be seeking to keep up with the
Soviet Union, which has been meeting with South African activists
across the political spectrum.
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen was scheduled to meet
in Rome with his Soviet counterpart this weekend to discuss the
South African changes and other developments.
</TEXT>
