<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-OldBasketball     05-27 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Old Basketball,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Viewers Watch NBA Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television viewers got to tune into their
first National Basketball Association game on Saturday, even if it
wasn't Saturday's game.
   While American viewers watched the Detroit Pistons-Chicago Bulls
on live network television, Soviet viewers had to settle for the
April 28 playoff contest between the Phoenix Suns and the Denver
Nuggets.
   Citizens here already were glued to their television sets to
watch the live coverage of the blunt and bellicose debate in their
newly formed parliament, the Congress of People's Deputies.
   As the Tass news agency noted, ``The whole of the Soviet Union
seems to be listening to radio and watching television sets,
displaying a huge interest in the work of the Congress of People's
Deputies under way in Moscow.''
   During the afternoon break in the congressional session,
however, state-run television broadcast a first-round game from the
NBA's Western Conference playoffs.
   During timeouts, soft-drink commercials featuring rock music and
dancers and highlights from other NBA games were shown. One
graphic, in English, told Soviets they were watching ``America's
Game.''
   As the hour-long break at the Kremlin drew to a close, the clock
in Phoenix showed three seconds left on the clock. Tom Chambers of
the Suns sank two foul shots, leading Phoenix to a 104-103 victory.
   As soon as the NBA game ended, Soviet television switched back
to the Palace of Congresses, and the proceedings chaired by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev resumed.
</TEXT>
