<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Soviet-Excerpts 1stLd-Writethru a0506 05-27 1123</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet-Excerpts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,1150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts From Speeches In Soviet Congress</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: ADDS more comments. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from speeches by members of the
Congress of People's Deputies after the defeat Saturday of the
Moscow reformists.
   Yuri Afanasyev, historian and leading figure in Memorial, a
society investigating the nation's Stalinist past:
   ``I had a depressing view of yesterday's work of our congress .
.. I thoroughly studied the list of candidates to the Supreme
Soviet (the full-time legislature elected by the congress). I must
say, and I am convinced of this, that if we take into account the
level of qualification compared to the tasks the Supreme Soviet
must decide ... we have formed a Brezhnev-Stalin Supreme Soviet.
   ``Now, about the majority that has formed at the congress. This
also depresses me ... I am addressing you all, the
aggressive-obedient majority, and you, Mikhail Sergeyevich
(Gorbachev), who is either attentively listening to the majority or
skillfully manipulating it. We can continue the work the same way,
we may be obedient ... but let us not forget those who sent us here
to the congress. And they sent us here not for that ... but to
drastically change the situation in the country.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Gavril Popov, liberal economist who was among those defeated:
   ``Deputies with a democratic orientation inevitably formed a
minority at the congress. We knew this. We had two choices as to
how to act. First, to try to play the role of opposition, and
second, to become involved in the constructive work of the
congress. We chose the second.
   ``But from the very beginning our work has met with some
disbelief and prejudice ... The documents we prepared have not been
copied so far and distributed among the deputies.
   ``It is becoming more and more evident that the apparatus
clearly wants to retaliate, clear that it wants to impose its own
way of work at the Congress. In these conditions it is impossible
to support the variant we first chose, it would not be understood
either by our country or by those who elected us.
   ``That is why we have to think about changing our positions. A
group of deputies considers it necessary to withdraw from the
Moscow delegation. We are going to form an ... independent deputies
group and invite all deputies to join us.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Yevgeny Meshalkin, Ministry of Health official in Siberia,
member of the Soviet Peace Committee:
   ``Those who are shouting about the disastrous situation did not
make any constructive suggestions, only demands for freedom. Why
don't they understand that we shouldn't behave like pirates, who
capture the ship of state, intend to break it into regions, small
craft they plan to sail in turbulent international waters?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ales Adamovich, a reformer famous for his novels about the
horrors of World War II in Byleorussia:
   ``I heard once, the people stopped drinking, sobered up a
little, looked around and asked, `Where is the czar?' What does it
mean, woke up? I witnessed myself during the war that people, very
often out of fear, went into a deep sleep ... It was a kind of
protective reaction of the body. That was how people were killed in
the 1920s, 1930s, 1940s, while the rest hibernated.
   ``And what did we find when we finally woke up? ... We realize
that after this long sleep we are not a modern state that sets an
example for others but an underdeveloped superstate which is losing
its ability to develop, to transform the mentally crippled
administrative child into a normal, social organism, to create a
working economy.
   ``People have great hopes for this congress. Does our work
justify their hopes? ... Won't we be forced to buy dark glasses, so
that at the end of the congress, we can slip like shadows through
the crowds which stand each day outside the Kremlin?
   ``The supreme power in the country should belong to the people,
but in reality it belongs to the party ... Without the power to
exercise control (over the budget and the party apparatus), the
congress won't be able to do much.
   ``And it goes without saying that the Congress of Deputies can
vote no-confidence in the government ... if it is obviously unable
to fulfill its duties.
   ``The windows of Western shops are full of goods. In our shop
windows, it would not be a bad idea to hang the portraits of
ministers, the agriculture minister in the butcher's shop, and so
on.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Leonid Kravchenko, director-general of the official news agency
Tass:
   ``At Tass we read attentively what the foreign press think about
the Congress. Already during the first day, the Western agencies
said radicals attempted to impose their point of view during the
discussion of procedural questions ... Frankly, I did not believe
in all this, but here is what we have now _ the speeches of
Afanasyev and Popov.
   ``I was amazed to hear such phrases as the Brezhnev-Stalin wing
... I know these comrades as persistent supporters of democracy.
And democracy implies patience for dissent. When such impatience is
shown toward an alternatively thinking majority ... I start to
doubt whether they persistently defend democracy.
   ``We have already answered the question `Who is guilty?'
completely enough. It is high time to answer the questions `What to
do?' and `How to do it?'''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Alexander N. Kraiko, non-party member, chief researcher at
Moscow aviation research institute, one of defeated reformers:
   ``Comrades, we should realize that Boris Yeltsin is the first
candidate of the Russian Federation. Not only was he elected by
five million Muscovites, but at almost 2,000 enterprises he was the
nominated candidate. In this case, it means that the Congress
neglects the opinion of the people, this is a discreditation of the
Congress ... In order not to have confrontation between us here and
between us and our people, the Presidium and our leadership have to
make necessary efforts to ensure that people like Boris Yeltsin
will take an active part in political life, not only at meetings,
but also here. I call on Mikhail Sergeyevich to do this.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Vladimir I. Kirillov, a young researcher at an institute in
Voronezh in southern Russia, who introduced himself as one of those
who gave Afanasyev a standing ovation:
   ``What is politics? It is the art of the possible ... We can now
see what our possibilities are here now. Here is Boris Yeltsin,
esteemed by me, who said that he had become unemployed (Yeltsin
last week quit his post as a first deputy construction minister.)
But I think that in our society he does a very important job. In
fact, he is determining the level of democracy in our society.
</TEXT>
