<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Congress 1stLd-Writethru   05-27 0884</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0598,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>Popular Reformers Ousted in Voting</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with Gorbachev comments, details of rally
and television coverage. CORRECTS first name of Lukyanov in 7th graf pvs.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Soviet congress dealt reformists a major
setback Saturday by rejecting maverick Boris Yeltsin and several
other prominent reformers who were seeking seats on the powerful
Supreme Soviet legislature.
   Thousands of Muscovites disappointed with the results gathered
for a rally that lasted through the night, and reformers in
congress vowed to form an opposition bloc to challenge the ruling
Communist Party.
   ``Down with the bloodsuckers who prey on the people!'' roared
one speaker at the rally.
   The furor was set off when the 2,250-seat Congress of People's
Deputies chose which of its members would serve on the new Supreme
Soviet, a full-time, 542-seat legislature.
   The election results and blunt debate that followed were
televised live.
   ``The supreme power in the country should belong to the people,
but in reality it belongs to the party,'' said Ales Adamovich, a
writer from Byelorussia and member of the congress.
   During a recess, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev sought to
reassure Soviets accustomed to decades of empty institutional
ritual that such clashes of opinion are to be expected.
   ``One need not panic,'' he said in remarks broadcast later on
national television. ``We cannot sit ceremoniously at the meetings
knowing that outside the hall, there is a stormy life with a lot of
problems.''
   Congressional deputies voted Friday to fill the Supreme Soviet
seats from among 573 candidates chosen by congress deputies from
their home regions. The results were announced Saturday.
   The congress rejected an 11th-hour attempt by Gorbachev to have
his protege, Anatoly I. Lukyanov, installed as vice president.
Weary deputies loudly complained the president's choice was being
forced through, and Gorbachev agreed to put the matter off until
Monday.
   In secret balloting for the Supreme Soviet, congressional
deputies elected a number of reform advocates from the tiny Baltic
republics, whose representatives nominated only as many candidates
as they had seats.
   Moscow deputies, however, nominated 55 candidates for their 29
seats, and Yeltsin and other prominent Moscow-based reformers were
among the losers. Also defeated were sociologist Tatyana
Zaslavskaya, economist Gavril Popov, advocate for the handicapped
Ilya Zaslavsky, historian Sergei Stankevich and biologist Alexei
Yablokov.
   Many old-style candidates, among them former cosmonaut Svetlana
Savitskaya, defeated the reformers.
   Yeltsin scored a landslide victory in Moscow in spring elections
for the Congress of People's Deputies and is among the country's
most popular political figures. He said he was saddened by the
results but indicated he may challenge Lukyanov for the vice
presidency.
   ``I must fight to the end,'' Yeltsin told reporters. ``I
wouldn't throw away any job.''
   Several thousand Muscovites gathered in a stadium parking lot to
protest Yeltsin's defeat. One speaker, teacher Vladimir Kuznetsov,
said he sent a telegram to Gorbachev telling him, ``I have less and
less respect for you and more and more'' for progressive Moscow
deputies.
   ``But is it really life, if it's in chains? But is it really an
election, if it's in fetters?'' read one placard.
   But in the Palace of Congresses, many deputies applauded as Yuri
A. Osipyan, chairman of the vote-counting commission, announced in
a droning voice the Moscow reformers' defeat.
   Leonid Kravchenko, director-general of the official news agency
Tass, defended the election.``For God's sake, let's not have chaos.
Everywhere and in everything there should be order.''
   Yevgeny Meshalkin, a Siberian health official, accused the
reformers of sour grapes.
   ``They find themselves in the minority, and the result cannot
satisfy them,'' he said. ``They instigate work aimed at breaking
the congress into factions.''
   Before the balloting in the first competitively elected
parliament in 70 years, some deputies complained the nominating
procedure had been rigged to keep party and government officials in
power.
   ``The apparatus has undoubtedly won,'' Popov declared to his
fellow deputies.
   He called on progressives nationwide to form an ``independent
deputies' group'' to fight Communist Party and state bureaucrats.
   Popov's declaration could lead to the first opposition faction
in a Soviet legislature, where for decades the Kremlin leadership
has imposed its will unimpeded by opposition.
   Yeltsin garnered a narrow majority, with 1,185 deputies
supporting him and 964 against, but he ran last among 12 candidates
for the 11 seats reserved for the Russian federation in one of the
Supreme Soviet's two chambers, the 271-seat Soviet of Nationalities.
   Yeltsin's defeat was a severe setback. His attacks on official
privilege, calls for a better life for average Soviets and his
suggestion that the party should discuss permitting a multi-party
democracy have made him a special target of the party's Old Guard.
   Vitaly I. Vorotnikov, the only member of the ruling party
Politburo to stand as a candidate and the president of the Russian
federation, outpolled Yeltsin with 1,388 votes.
   During the afternoon break, Soviet viewers got to tune into
their first National Basketball Association game _ even if it was a
month old.
   Soviet viewers had to settle for the April 28 playoff contest
between the Phoenix Suns and the Denver Nuggets.
   As the break at the Kremlin drew to a close, Tom Chambers of the
Suns sank two foul shots, leading Phoenix to a 104-103 victory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
