<DOCNO> AP890527-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0575 05-27 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0575,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Assures Pope of Progress in Reducing Arms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds. New throughout with details from papal meeting; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush assured Pope John Paul II on
Saturday that the United States is making progress to reduce
armaments and is committed to helping spur economic and political
reforms in the pontiff's homeland and elsewhere across Eastern
Europe.
   The pope, after nearly an hour of private talks with Bush in the
papal library, praised the American president's commitment ``to
liberate the youth of America from the destructive forces of drug
abuse'' and to alleviate poverty.
   The pope called for renewed efforts to battle the ``moral
crisis'' afflicting society all over the world.
   A senior Vatican official, who requested anonymity, said the
sweeping changes in communist Eastern Europe and the civil war in
Lebanon were the main themes of the private talks between the two
men.
   ``While we are still far from realizing the Biblical injunction
to turn our swords into plowshares, we have made progress in
reducing armaments, and in decreasing the threat of war,'' Bush
told the pope.
   Turning to the civil war in Lebanon, Bush said, ``We've heard
your eloquent appeals for an end to the violence in Lebanon, and my
heart, too, aches for the people of that once peaceful land.''
   The Vatican visit came near the end of the first full day of
Bush's trip, which takes him to Brussels on Sunday for a summit
with NATO allies divided over how best to proceed on arms talks
with the Soviet Union.
   As a Pole and head of a church that plays an important role in
eastern Europe, John Paul has an unusual vantage from which to
offer advice on the changes taking place in the region.
   Both the pope and the president recalled passages from Bush's
inauguration speech. The pope approved Bush's declaration that the
only proper use of power is to serve people, and Bush said anew
that ``a new breeze is blowing'' across the world and bringing
greater freedom.
   ``May God bless America, and make her strong in her defense of
human dignity and in her service to life,'' including the life of
``the weakest and most defenseless ones, those as yet unborn,'' the
pope said, repeating an anti-abortion plea he also made at the end
of his last U.S. pilgrimage in 1987.
   Bush thanked him ``for this opportunity to visit with you to
share in your wisdom, and I assure you of our intent to work ever
more fervently for peace, justice and freedom throughout the
world.''
   Bush, scheduled to visit Poland in July, noted the accords
between the government and the opposition aimed at providing
greater freedom and the communist state's agreement to give the
Roman Catholic Church legal status.
   ``This triumph represents the first full normalization of
church-state relations in any communist state _ and it is a tribute
to your enduring commitment to freedom,'' Bush said.
   `'As you know, I recently announced a package of financial
measures that signaled our active engagement in encouraging
economic and political reform in Poland and elsewhere in eastern
Europe,'' he added.
   The president's wife, Barbara, dressed in a black suit and small
black veil, joined her husband and the pope after their private
talk. The Bushes later toured the Sistine Chapel together.
   A 33-member presidential entourage also got to meet the pope,
including the military officer who carries the black briefcase
known as the ``football'' that contains the codes to be used in
event of a nuclear attack.
   When the officer lined up to shake hands with the pontiff, he
left the briefcase at his seat.
   Later, addressing 250 American seminarians, Bush said he and the
pope discussed ``broad questions of peace, freedom and justice as
they apply or ought to apply all over the world.''
   ``It's a talk that I'll long remember,'' said Bush, an
Episcopalian. ``I leave once again inspired by his moral and
spiritual leadership.''
   The seminarians burst into a chorus of ``God Bless America''
after Bush spoke.
   As the pope and Bush talked, U.S. Secretary of State James Baker
and Brent Scowcroft, the national security adviser, met with
Vatican Secretary of State Cardinal Agostino Casaroli and other top
Vatican officials.
   John Paul will meet with Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev here in
November, the first time a Soviet Communist party chief will sit
down with the leader of the world's 850 million Roman Catholics.
   The pope has spoken favorably if cautiously of Gorbachev's
policies of glasnost and perestroika to open up and reform Soviet
society. John Paul has expressed strong support of attempts by the
independent Polish labor union Solidarity to do the same in his
homeland.
   No world leader encounters so wide a range of visitors as John
Paul. On the eve of the Bush visit, he met with an official
Bulgarian delegation, Lebanon-bound Cardinal John O'Connor of New
York and a Cuban official who reportedly came with an invitation
for the first-ever papal visit to the communist island nation.
</TEXT>
