<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-27 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Rules Out Compropomise on Proposed Soviet-U.S. Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Saturday
he opposed postponing proposed U.S.-Soviet talks on short-range
nuclear weapons as a possible compromise in the dispute within NATO
over the issue.
   In a surprise move, Kohl flew later to the Netherlands for talks
with Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers over the division in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Lubbers has offered to mediate the dispute, in which West
Germany is trying to persuade the United States to agree to early
talks with the Soviets on short-range atomic arsenals.
   A government spokesman told The Associated Press Kohl's talks
with Lubbers were part of an earlier planned meeting with Holland's
governing Christian Democrats to discuss a number of topics. But
there had been no announcement of Kohl's plans to confer with
Lubbers.
   Speaking to reporters in the southern city of Nuremberg before
leaving for the Netherlands, Kohl said superpower negotiations on
the short-range atomic arsenals ``cannot be postponed into the
distant future.''
   ``We are the front-line country in NATO. It is clear that we
should be speaking up for our interests,'' Kohl said.
   The United States, seeking to avert a NATO split, has reversed a
firm stand against such negotiations and agreed to talks with the
Soviets at an unspecified time on reducing the number of
short-range nuclear weapons.
   Also Saturday, Kohl's junior coalition partners made a veiled
threat to pull out of the government if the chancellor agreed to
unacceptable compromises on the issue during NATO summit that opens
Monday.
   Kohl is caught between liberal elements within his coalition and
conservatives who fear the internal feud endangers the Western
alliance.
   Public opinion polls show most Germans want the Lance atomic
rockets removed from German soil rather than modernized, as NATO
advocates.
   Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg reiterated West Germany's
call for U.S. talks with the Soviets on the issue, the Bild
newspaper reported. But it said Stoltenberg also noted West Germany
can't formulate European defense policy alone.
   ``We must connect our interests to the clear goal of coming to a
common position within NATO through give and take,'' Soltenberg
said in the interview to be published Sunday.
   Bonn and Washington have tried to heal their rift over Kohl's
call for early talks on the short-range missiles. The United States
and Britain say the talks should not occur while the Warsaw Pact
has superiority in conventional forces.
   West German newspapers said Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher on Tuesday threatened to pull his minority Free Democratic
Party out of the governming coalition if Kohl softens his stand.
   Members of the coalition are Kohl's Christian Democratic Union,
its conservative Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union,
and the business-oriented Free Democrats.
   Some members of Kohl's government, including Stoltenberg,
reportedly have been angered by Genscher's aggressiveness in the
NATO dispute. Newspaper reports said Stoltenberg noted Washington
has agreed in principle to start up negotiations on short-range
nuclear weapons and the question now is when those talks should
begin.
</TEXT>
