<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Communist     05-27 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Communist,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leader Finds Bush More Accessible in Rome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the head of the Italian Communist party visited
Washington two weeks ago he didn't get to meet with any
administration officials. On Saturday he got to shake hands with
President Bush.
   Achille Occhetto joined other Italian leaders in greeting the
president at a glittering state dinner.
   Meanwhile, out on the streets of Rome, leftist demonstrators
protesting the Bush visit clashed with police, and 18 were detained
at the central police headquarters for questioning.
   A band of about 50 demonstrators hurled cobblestones and fired
steel balls from slingshots at riot police, who fought back with
truncheons, the Italian News Agency ANSA reported.
   Three police officers were reported slightly injured and a
60-year-old Italian woman was hospitalized with leg and face
bruises after being accidentally caught up in the melee a mile from
the Vatican, where Bush was meeting with Pope John Paul II.
   The protest was organized by small leftist groups including the
Proletarian Democracy Party upset about plans for Italy to host a
unit of F-16 fighters being forced out of Spain.
   The 120 guests at the black-tie dinner for Bush in the 16th
century Villa Madama included the leaders of major parties invited
by Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita, a Christian Democrat.
   Occhetto not only got to shake hands with the president, but was
seated next to Ruth Rabb, wife of U.S. Ambassador Maxwell Rabb.
   During the toasts, Mrs. Rabb and Occhetto clinked glasses and
smiled. Occhetto also applauded after a vibrantly pro-Atlantic
speech by De Mita, who warned against neutralism in the face of
Soviet offers to cut armaments.
   De Mita also offered his support to the United States in its
efforts to re-establish democracy in Panama and condemned ``the
serious violation of the rules of democracy recently perpetrated by
General (Manuel) Noriega.''
   Occhetto, 53, made the first visit to the United States ever by
an Italian Communist Party head seeking to present a new image of
the largest communist party in the West and Italy's No. 2 party.
   The party has been locked out of the Christian
Democrat-dominated government since 1947, and successive U.S.
administrations have regarded the party with suspicion. In past
years, some members have been denied visas.
   Occhetto got a visa and met with leaders of the House and
Senate. But the government called the visit ``private'' and
arranged no meetings with administration officials.
</TEXT>
