<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     05-27 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says `Stormy Life' to be Expected in Soviet Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN_THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev took a break from
fierce parliamentary debate Saturday to reassure Soviets used to
empty institutional ritual that the open clash of opinions was
perfectly normal.
   ``One need not panic,'' he told a knot of fellow
parliamentarians during a recess at the Congress of People's
Deputies at the Kremlin's Palace of Congresses.
   ``We cannot sit ceremoniously at the meetings knowing that
outside the hall there is a stormy life with a lot of problems,''
Gorbachev said.
   His comments were carried on national television. Soviet
citizens have been keenly following the fiery proceedings in the
congress, a sharp contrast to the traditional rubber-stamp
practices.
   Lawmakers used to meet in Moscow for only three or four days a
year, unanimously pass legislation put before them by the Communist
Party leadership and deliver ovations to top officials.
   On Saturday legislators made statements that would have been
inconceivable at an official forum even a year ago. The statements
included Byelorussian writer Ales Adamovich's claim that power in
the Soviet Union is held not by the people but by the Communist
Party.
   Even Gorbachev fell victim to the new combativeness of Soviet
parliamentarians when, in an 11th-hour move, he tried to get the
congress to re-elect his protege, Anatoly I. Lukyanov, to the vice
presidency.
   Deputies objected that they were tired after three days of
debate, and wanted more than one candidate to pick from. Gorbachev
backed down, and the congress adjourned until Monday.
   In informal talks with other deputies, Gorbachev said a clash of
views was normal but legislators should respect those they disagree
with.
   ``It is all right that passions are stirring,'' he said. ``When
people talk about the country, the people, their fate, business,
what to do to improve the situation, we have to show respect.''
   Gorbachev said Soviets have been sending letters and telegrams
asking ``what is the congress doing?''
   ``At first glance, the work of the congress might look
disorganized, deputies lacking political culture, even starting to
place others in various categories,'' he said, but the newly
created parliament is only beginning.
   ``The most important thing is to move things,'' he said.
</TEXT>
