<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-27 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arctic Chill Hits Northwest; Cold Front Sweeps Through East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Arctic air plunged south from Canada on Saturday, bringing
bitter winds and the possibility of snowfall to the Northwest, and
another cold front accompanied by showers and thunderstorms swept
through the eastern United States.
   Much of the rest of the nation, however, enjoyed sunny skies.
   In the Northwest, the bitter winds were expected to bring snow
to higher elevations through Sunday; and a snow advisory was posted
for the Cascade Mountains of Oregon.
   Cloudy skies hung over much of the region early Saturday
afternoon. Northern California and southwestern Oregon were
drenched with numerous showers.
   A cold front in the eastern United States brought showers and
thunderstorms to the middle Atlantic coast region and parts of New
England. A thunderstorm in Millville, N.J., whipped winds to 48 mph.
   The same cold front sent showers through southern Arkansas into
north- central Texas.
   The rest of the nation had dry weather, with clear skies from
the desert Southwest through the middle and upper Mississippi
Valley and to the Ohio Valley and the upper Great Lakes.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 97 degrees at Charleston, S.C.,
and Jacksonville, Fla.
   The low Saturday was 27 degrees at Yellowstone National Park,
Wyo.
   Sunday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
across the middle and upper Mississippi Valley and the northern
Plains region; showers from the upper half of the Rocky Mountain
region to the northern and central Pacific Coast, with snow
possible in higher elevations; widely scattered thunderstorms
through the Florida peninsula; windy conditions to the upper half
of the Mississippi Valley; and fair to partly sunny skies across
the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were forecast above 80 degrees from Southern
California through the southern and central Plains region to the
southern Atlantic Coast; in the 90s from the southwestern deserts
across much of Texas to the Florida peninsula; in the 60s from
upper Michigan to New England; below 70 degrees from the northern
and central Pacific Coast to Montana; and in the 50s and upper 40s
from the northern Rockies to the northern half of the Plateau
region.
</TEXT>
