<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Anti-Semitism     05-27 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Anti-Semitism,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Community Taking Court Action Over Legislator's Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frankfurt's Jewish community said
Saturday it is taking court action against a city councilman from
an ultrarightist party for reportedly saying ``Jews are plundering
us again.''
   The city prosecutor's office has said it is investigating
legislator Erich Gutjahr for possibly violating German laws with
his alleged statements, printed Friday in the Frankfurt Allgemeine
newspaper.
   In a telex to the news media on Saturday, the Frankfurt Jewish
community said it was starting its own action to try to get a court
to bring charges against Gutjahr, saying he had ``stirred up
anti-Semitic prejudices.''
   Under West German law, citizens have standing to file a
complaint asking justice officials to bring someone to trial.
   Several members of the city council on Friday demanded the
resignation of Gutjahr, a 78-year-old member of the rightist
National Party of Germany (NPD).
   The NPD, whose views are often likened to those of German
neo-Nazi groups, won seven city council seats in local elections
last March, giving the ultrarightist party a minority voice in the
body.
   Gutjahr was quoted as saying, ``Jews have bought up half of the
city. The Jews are plundering us again. Something must be done
about this.''
   The elderly councilman said he was not anti-Semitic and only
wants to protect ``German interests,'' the Allgemeine reported.
</TEXT>
