<FIRST>r a AM-Queen'sVisit     05-27 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Queen's Visit,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Queen Sees Foal, Mare at Lane's End Farm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDWAY, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II of England, whose pursuits
include horse racing, got her first look Saturday at a month-old
foal that she is boarding at a Kentucky farm.
   The queen ``commented on how frisky and bouncy the foal was,''
said Mike Cline, the manager of Lane's End farm. ``She remarked
about how much personality the foal has.''
   The queen was in Kentucky to look at five mares she is boarding
at the Lane's End and Mill Ridge farms, and to see some stallions
for possible breeding.
   Lane's End farmhands Tim Thore and Callan Strouss brought the
young thoroughbred and Highclere, who foaled the colt on April 29,
into a walking area for the queen to examine.
   The playful foal pranced around his mother while the queen
looked on, apparently delighted. The queen patted the mare and gave
her some mints. But she stayed clear of the foal.
   This is the third time in five years that the queen has stayed
at the neatly manicured farm, located about 10 miles west of
Lexington on gently rolling pastureland.
   ``I think most of us are relaxed with her being here,'' said
Cline. ``Since she's a horsewoman, it's been easy being around
her.''
   Racing manager Lord Carnarvon, who accompanied the queen, said
she breeds horses in Kentucky for speed in races that range from 1\
miles to 1{ miles. He said she is putting together next year's
mating list.
   After her arrival Friday afternoon, the queen attended a small
dinner at Lane's End that included British Ambassador Antony
Acland. She will return to England on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
