<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-O'Connor 1stLd-Writethru a0601 05-27 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-O'Connor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal O'Connor Arrives in Lebanon on Hostage Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts 4th graf to CORRECT that Waite not a cleric but a church
envoy.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BKIRKI, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York
arrived Saturday on a visit aimed at focusing the world's attention
on foreign hostages held in Lebanon and on the bitter fighting
between Christian and Moslem forces.
   O'Connor said he did not come to Lebanon to negotiate on behalf
of the United States but he would gladly meet with the hostages,
even if that meant entering the Moslem sector of Beirut.
   ``I hope that they can hear my voice or can see me or can read
that the people of our country have not forgotten them. They're in
our prayers,'' he said.
   Among the missing foreigners is Anglican church envoy Terry
Waite, who came on a mission to try to gain the release of
hostages. He disappeared in Beirut on Jan. 20, 1988, after leaving
his hotel for a meeting with captors of some of the victims.
   Before O'Connor arrived, Syrian gunners shelled the Christian
coastline north of Beirut, despite an appeal by Arab leaders to
observe a cease-fire.
   More than 350 people have been killed and nearly 1,400 wounded
since March 8 when the latest round of fighting broke in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war.
   O'Connor said the fighting in Lebanon, in which the Christian
forces are heavily outnumbered and outgunned by the Syrians and
their allies, has been largely ignored by the U.S. and world media.
   ``This is extraordinary, that a nation is being destroyed, a
religious body is being almost obliterated and an organism where so
many religions lived harmoniously is being torn apart and we really
haven't responded,'' he said.
   O'Connor, who came in his role as President of the Roman
Catholic Near West Welfare Association, flew in from Larnaca,
Cyprus, aboard a military helicopter provided by Christian leader
Gen. Michel Aoun.
   The helicopter landed after sunset at the hilltop monastery of
Bkirki, seat of Maronite Catholic Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, nine
miles north of Beirut.
   Sfeir, spiritual head of the Maronite sect that has dominated
the government since Lebanon gained independence from France in
1943, will be O'Connor's host during his three-day visit.
   O'Connor, who ignored State Department objections to the trip,
stopped in Rome on Friday for talks with Pope John Paul II. He came
to Bkirki with a Vatican passport and visa to sidestep a U.S. ban
on travel to Lebanon.
   He told reporters in Larnaca the pope is distressed about the
Lebanese crisis. ``I haven't seen him nearly so anguished about
anything else as he is about Lebanon,'' O'Connor said. ``It's just
eating away at him.''
   Asked whether he was afraid to be in Lebanon, O'Connor smiled
and said: ``No I'm not. Why should I be?''
   There are 15 foreigners, including nine Americans, held hostage
in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Asked if he would seek to free the hostages, O'Connor, who
visited Lebanon in June 1986, said: ``I'll certainly say what I
said last time I was here about the American hostages and all
hostages. I'm not an ambassador from the United States. I'm simply
a priest, a churchman.''
   He said, ``I'm not here as a negotiator ... If their captors
would permit me to see them, then I'd be very happy to see them and
do anything I could to help them.'' Asked whether he would cross
Beirut's dividing Green Line to the Moslem sector, where most of
the hostages are believed held, the cardinal said: ``I'll be going
to wherever Patriarch Sfeir thinks I should go.''
   Officials said O'Connor was scheduled to drive to west Beirut to
meet with acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a Moslem
Cabinet vying for legitimacy with a Christian government headed by
Aoun.
   The cardinal was scheduled to meet Sunday with Aoun at the
shell-battered presidential palace in Baabda, five miles east of
Beirut.
</TEXT>
