<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-SoccerViolence     05-27 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soccer Violence,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>250 Soccer Fans Arrested in Scotland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soccer fans clashed Saturday in the
city center and the streets surrounding a Glasgow stadium before,
during and after a game between Scotland and England, and police
reported more than 250 arrests.
   The annual England-Scotland game, the oldest rivalry in
international soccer, often has been the setting for fan violence
in recent years. Police in Glasgow had expected problems and made
special plans for controlling hooliganism surrounding the game.
   ``There were clashes between rival groups and police stepped in
quickly to quell any disturbances and make arrests,'' said
Strathclyde Police spokesman Ralph Howden. ``We generally have kept
on top of things.''
   Howden said about 100 fans were arrested before the match at
Hampden Park stadium, mostly for minor offenses.
   There were no serious injuries reported, he said, and the only
report of property damage was of a broken pub window.
   Police later reported more than 150 related arrests in the city
center.
   Soccer hooliganism, a persistent problem for years, has become
particularly sensitive recently with the involvement of British
fans in the May 29, 1985 Heysel stadium riots in Brussels, in which
39 people were killed.
   On April 15, 95 fans were killed at Sheffield's Hillsborough
stadium when police permitted shoving fans into an already crowded
standing area, creating a fatal crush.
</TEXT>
