<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 1906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hijack-Interpreter     05-27 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack-Interpreter,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passengers Praise Interpreter's Work During Hijacking</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The baggage area for American Airlines Flight 1098
was swarming with passengers, but there was no mistaking the man of
the hour _ Eli Infante, who served as interpreter Saturday when
their plane was hijacked.
   ``He's a hero!'' one of his fellow passengers shouted.
   Surrounded by reporters, the Miami man smiled modestly and
remained unruffled as he did throughout the hijacking.
   ``He was great,'' agreed Albert Saghian, a ladies fashion
salesman from Los Angeles.
   Infante's wife Silvia sat patiently while her husband, a
33-year-old sales representative for Minolta Business Systems, told
his story again and again.
   ``I thought I wasn't going to get home,'' said Mrs. Infante, who
with her husband was returning from a company-paid vacation in
Hawaii. ``The beginning was pretty difficult because we didn't know
where we were standing. All they would say was the individual
wanted to go to Havana.''
   Mrs. Infante, 28, said she was proud of her husband's behavior
as he relayed messages between the crew and the Spanish-speaking
hijacker, identified by the FBI as Pedro Rene Comas-Banos, an
escaped mental patient who emigrated from Cuba in the Mariel
boatlift.
   ``I thought he handled it very good, kept himself calm,'' she
said. ``I think that if he would have been tense, it would have
made it worse.''
   She said Infante persuaded the man to release children from the
plane and tried to get him to let the women go _ or at least his
own wife.
   Comas-Banos allowed children the leave the parked Boeing 727,
and Infante and other negotiators talked him into surrendering
minutes later. Infante offered to accompany the man from the plane,
but the crew wouldn't allow it.
   Lenny Anyia, a high school math teacher in Hawthorne, Calif.,
sat across from Infante and Comas-Banos and said the hijacker
didn't act strangely.
   ``I dismissed him almost from the moment we took off,'' he said,
adding, ``Eli, he was great.''
   Mrs. Infante said she and her husband would pick up their two
small sons at her sister-in-law's house, then go home and rest.
   ``Thank God it's a long weekend,'' she said.
   When asked if she would fly again, she laughed and replied,
``It'll be a long time.''
 
</TEXT>
