<FIRST>u a AM-Hijack 5thLd-Writethru a0620 05-27 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0620,0908</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jetliner Hijacked on Dallas-Miami Flight; All Aboard Safe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of suspect's mental history,
suspect charged, flight number; CORRECTS that pants were olive-drab, sted
camouflage. Edits to tighten and delete outdated material.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY24; LaserPhotos MH5, MH6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban immigrant who escaped from a mental
hospital tried to hijack an American Airlines jetliner to Cuba on
Saturday, but he surrendered after the plane landed at Miami,
authorities said.
   The Boeing 727 carrying 157 passengers and crew en route from
Dallas to Miami was diverted toward Cuba temporarily before heading
back to its original destination. The hijacker was armed with a
starter's pistol and two knives, but no one was injured.
   He was identified as Pedro Rene Comas-Banos, 37, who came to the
United States exactly nine years ago Saturday as part of the Mariel
boatlift, said FBI agent William Gavin.
   The suspect has a history of mental problems, most recently
escaping from an institution in the Los Angeles area, Gavin said,
adding that the date of that escape is not yet known.
   ``He has been living since that time in the Los Angeles area and
reportedly has a son in Cuba and has expressed interest in
returning to Cuba,'' Gavin said.
   Before going to Los Angeles, Gavin said, Comas-Banos escaped
from St. Elizabeths Hospital in Washington, D.C., where John
Hinckley, who attempted to assassinate President Reagan in 1981, is
held. Comas-Banos was there from 1980 to 1982.
   ``He's a very confused individual, not at all crystal clear and
cogent,'' Gavin said. ``His mind keeps changing.''
   Dressed in olive-drab fatigues and a bomber-type jacket, the
sandy-haired Comas-Banos boarded an American Airlines flight in Los
Angeles on Saturday morning and then transferred to the Miami-bound
flight in Dallas, Gavin said.
   ``After the flight left the ground on its way to Miami, he
produced a demand note and said he wanted to be taken to Havana,''
Gavin said. Speaking only Spanish, the hijacker told the flight
crew he was carrying a bomb in his briefcase, which actually
contained a starter's pistol used in track races, two pocket knives
and a pair of scissors.
   The pilot turned back toward Miami after reporting he didn't
have enough fuel to get to Havana, which Gavin said was true.
`There was no bluff here this morning,'' Gavin said. The plane
never entered Cuban airspace.
   Ninety minutes after Flight 1098 parked in a remote corner of
Miami International Airport, Comas-Banos allowed children to leave
the jet and then gave himself up, Gavin said.
   ``All the passengers are off and safe,'' said Federal Aviation
Administration spokesman Jack Barker.
   Comas-Banos was charged with air piracy and taken to the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in Dade County pending a hearing
Tuesday before a federal magistrate, Gavin said. If convicted,
Comas-Banos faces a maximum penalty of life in prison.
   One passenger, Eli Infante, 33, of Miami, said he served as
interpreter between the hijacker and crew.
   ``I thought I was going to get shot,'' Infante said.
   Asked why Comas-Banos gave up, Infante said, ``I guess he got
tired. We kept telling him we would not take off with passengers
aboard.''
   Infante's wife, Silvia, 28, described Comas-Banos as ``very
tense. He was sweating a lot and walking back and forth saying he
had accomplices. But we never saw anybody but him.''
   Describing Comas-Banos' surrender, Mrs. Infante said ``he
collapsed and everybody jumped on him'' as he left the back of the
jet.
   At one point, the FAA and the airline had said there might be
more than one hijacker, but they said later that that was never
confirmed.
   Robert Baker, senior vice president of operations at American
Airlines, said the hijacker claimed to have confederates aboard the
plane, and the other passengers were being interviewed and the
plane checked for weapons.
   FAA officials said passengers left the aircraft by rear stairs,
and their carry-on luggage was checked by officers with police dogs.
   Flight 1098, carrying 150 passengers and a crew of seven, left
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport about 8 a.m. EDT and was
scheduled to land at Miami at about 10:30 a.m.
   ``Approximately 15 miles north of Miami ... the pilot reported
he had a passenger who wanted to go to Havana,'' said FAA spokesman
Bob Buckhorn in Washington.
   ``The aircraft circled Miami for approximately 20 minutes and
then turned south. Approximately 60 miles south of Miami, the
aircraft turned north again,'' Buckhorn said.
   The Coast Guard was notified of an air emergency shortly before
11 a.m. as the jet flew over the Atlantic Ocean. Ditching ``was a
concern at one point in time,'' said law enforcement duty officer
David Newton.
   In Miami, Metro-Dade police sent a special-weapons and tactics
team to the airport, and the FBI was on the scene.
   During the 1960s and 1970s, there were a rash of hijackings or
attempted hijackings to Cuba before the institution of security
measures at airports and the cooperation of Cuban authorities
stemmed the tide.
   Last December, a Cuban exile tried to hijack a TWA airliner to
Cuba on a flight from San Juan, Puerto Rico, to Miami, but the
aircraft landed on Grand Turk Island instead with the hijacker
thinking he was on the ground in Havana.
</TEXT>
