<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Rally     05-27 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rally,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disappointed Muscovites Rally After Congress Session</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several thousand disappointed Muscovites gathered
in a stadium parking lot Saturday night and denounced the rejection
by the new Congress of reform candidates who ran for seats in the
standing legislature.
   Many people in the crowd shouted slogans supporting maverick
Communist Boris Yeltsin.
   ``The majority of the people is for the minority of the
deputies,'' one banner said. Another placard said: ``But is it
really life, if it's in chains? But is it really an election, if
it's in fetters?''
   Vladimir Kuznetsov, a teacher, said he sent a telegram to
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev telling him, ``I have less and less
respect for you and more and more'' for Moscow's reform deputies.
   He was applauded when he told the crowd, ``Down with the
bloodsuckers who prey on the people!''
   ``Now we see we can't set our hopes on Gorbachev or on the
Congress,'' another speaker told the rally, which went on past
midnight.
   In nationwide balloting last spring and scores of runoff
elections, 2,250 members were elected to the Congress of People's
Deputies. On Saturday the deputies elected members to the
full-time, 542-seat Supreme Soviet legislature. Yeltsin and other
prominent Moscow reformers were defeated.
   Gorbachev's handling of Saturday's session drew comments from
people at the rally.
   ``Did you see how Gorbachev led the Congress? Like a conductor,
waggling his fingers,'' one man said.
   When an organizer asked the crowd to behave more ``ethically''
and stop trying to grab the microphone a woman said, ``What about
Gorbachev's `ethical' behavior?''
   A member of the Moscow branch of the Democratic Union, which
helped organize the rally, said he was disgusted when he saw the
list of deputies elected to the Supreme Soviet. ``They're all the
familiar faces I've been seeing for the last two years,'' he said.
``What prevented them two years ago from making the reforms they're
supposed to start doing now?''
   The rally, held in the Luzhniki sports complex, was approved by
Moscow authorities as a gathering for public expressions on the
Congress.
   Police did not intervene and an organizer said authorities even
offered the use of a public address system.
</TEXT>
