<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Foley     05-27 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Denies `Crisis' in Democratic Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley said
Saturday the Democratic Party and Congress were not ``in a crisis''
despite the ethics controversies that have ensnared Speaker Jim
Wright and Rep. Tony Coelho.
   The Washington congressman said he tried to persuade Coelho, who
as majority whip is the No. 3 House Democrat, not to resign from
Congress because of a pending ethics investigation into personal
finances.
   But he said his California colleague told him his decision to
quit was irreversible.
   ``There is an environment of very intense scrutiny and focus on
us,'' Foley told reporters as he shook hands during the annual Old
Mill Days parade in Oakesdale, about 45 miles south of Spokane.
   ``In recent weeks and months, the focus has been so intense, it
has created a mood ... that I hope will soon change to focus on the
legislative issues,'' said Foley, who is favored to succeed Wright
should the speaker resign as expected next week.
   ``I hope the focus of the media will come back to those issues
for which we were elected to undertake.''
   The 13-term congressman, who later was keynote speaker at a
Democratic Party fund-raiser in Spokane, said the ethics issues
have not hurt the Democrats or Congress.
   ``We are not in a crisis. The Democratic Party, or the Congress
are not in a crisis,'' he told reporters. ``We're going to address
ourselves to the legislative issues that face the country.
   ``We'll resolve the leadership issues very soon and we'll go on
and have a very important and meaningful Congress,'' he said.
   He noted Coelho, who had been expected to be a candidate to
replace Foley as majority leader, continued to deny he had violated
any House ethics standards.
   Coelho has ``had a brilliant record as chairman of the campaign
committee and as the party whip, and I think he'll be deeply missed
by his colleagues and by the constituents he served so well,''
Foley said.
   Coelho told colleagues late Friday that he intends to resign
from Congress next month rather than endure a protracted ethics
investigation. Coelho has come under criticism for his personal
business dealings, particularly the handling of a $100,000
investment in junk bonds.
</TEXT>
