<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Indy500Festivities     05-27 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indy 500 Festivities,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estimated 325,000 View Parade Featuring Indianapolis 500 Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Race car drivers accompanied by floats,
bands, giant balloons and other celebrities took a slow turn
through town Saturday, a day before the somewhat faster-paced
Indianapolis 500.
   Singing cowboy Gene Autry, the 81-year-old grand marshal, led
the parade through downtown Indianapolis before an estimated crowd
of 325,000 people.
   More than 100 floats, bands and other entries participated in
the 500 Festival Memorial Parade, including the drivers who will
roar around the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Sunday.
   Other participants included Gov. Evan Bayh; Autry, the
actor-movie maker, and his sidekick, Pat Buttram; Misty Rowe of
television's Hee Haw; political humorist Mark Russell; actor and
race car enthusiast James Garner; and ``Airplane'' star Robert Hays.
   The parade theme, ``The American West _ From the Frontier to the
Future,'' heralded the opening of the Eiteljorg Museum of American
Indian and Western Art next month and had several floats displaying
Conestoga wagons and space ships.
   An estimated 40,000 people lined the parade route in reserved
seats and thousands more watched from crowded sidewalks, office and
apartment windows and rooftops.
   ``We're parade people,'' said one spectator, Ruth Wilson, of
Phoenix, Ariz. ``We came to see the drivers for this one.''
</TEXT>
