<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Newborn     05-27 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Newborn,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jazz Pianist Dead At 57</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phineas Newborn Jr., who was considered
one of the top jazz pianists during his prime but who never gained
widespread acclaim, has died at the age of 57.
   Newborn was found dead Friday at his home. The cause of death
has not been released.
   Irvin Salky, Newborn's agent and friend, said X-rays six weeks
ago showed a growth on one of Newborn's lungs.
   ``We found him slumped over in a chair on the front porch,''
said his brother, Calvin Newborn. Newborn was taken to the Regional
Medical Center where he was pronounced dead.
   ``In his prime, he was one of the three greatest jazz pianists
of all time, right up there with Bud Powell and Art Tatum,'' said
jazz critic Leonard Feather, a columnist for Downbeat magazine and
the Los Angeles Times.
   Newborn's work was best known in the mid 1950s and 1960s.
Although he was not a celebrity, he was highly regarded by jazz
aficionados.
   His albums included ``A World of Piano,'' ``The Newborn Touch,''
``The Great Piano of Phineas'' and ``Piano Artistry of Phineas
Newborn.''
   Survivors include his mother, daughters, son and two
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
