<FIRST>r a AM-House-Atwater     05-27 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-Atwater,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Chairman Demands Congressional Vote in Ethics Cases</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress owes the public ``an up or down
vote'' on alleged ethics violations by two Democratic leaders even
if they step down, Republican National Committee Chairman Lee
Atwater said Saturday.
   Atwater said the resignation of House Majority Whip Tony Coelho
and the anticipated resignation of Speaker Jim Wright does not mean
the ethics investigations should be halted and the allegations
dropped.
   ``If I were a member of Congress, I would want an opportunity to
vote on these Wright and Coelho matters,'' he said. ``What would
disappoint me would be if these things are just kind of brushed
aside.''
   Atwater, who said he was taken by surprise by Coelho's decision
to step down, urged Congress to improve its tarnished image. ``It's
very dangerous and very unhealthy for the American people to have
such a bad attitude about one of our institutions,'' he said.
   The GOP chairman said he's been avoiding attempts to make
political hay out of the Wright and Coelho problems. He would not
say whether he expects congressional ethics to be a dominant issue
in the 1990 elections.
   ``I've been following the Napoleonic maxim, which is `never
interfere with the enemy when he's in the process of destroying
himself,''' Atwater said.
   Atwater, who managed George Bush's presidential campaign last
year, was in Maine for an afternoon fund-raising reception at the
Cape Elizabeth home of House Minority Leader Mary Clark Webster.
</TEXT>
