<FIRST>r a AM-Biden-Plagiarism     05-27 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Biden-Plagiarism,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Clears Biden of Law School Plagiarism Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Joseph Biden was cleared of
allegations that he committed plagiarism in law school by a panel
under the authority of the Delaware Supreme Court, The (Wilmington)
News Journal reported.
   In its Sunday editions, the newspaper also said Biden has
received a clean bill of health from his physician following two
life-threatening brain aneurysms in 1987.
   The Delaware Democrat pulled out of the 1988 presidential
campaign following accusations that he quoted British Labour Party
leader Neil Kinnock without attribution and had plagiarized an
article while attending Syracuse University's law school.
   Biden called his failure to attribute the Kinnock quotes an
oversight.
   The alleged law school plagiarism involved an essay Biden wrote
in 1965 for an introductory class on legal methodology.
   The senator ended his presidential campaign Sept. 23, 1987, and
notified the state Supreme Court of the plagiarism allegations
later that year.
   The court's Board on Professional Responsibility, consisting of
lawyers and non-lawyers, ruled on Dec. 21, 1987, that Biden had not
violated any rules.
   Biden said he decided not to publicize the ruling, which was
confidential. ``I didn't know what to do with it,'' Biden said.
``Why didn't I hold a press conference? I guess I had in the back
of my mind ... this was more of a personal vindication than a
political one.''
   He added, however, that he finally decided to divulge it because
he expected ``somebody would go back someday and check. And I knew
there was a hard record there.''
   L. Susan Faw, independent disciplinary counsel for the board,
confirmed that the ruling had cleared Biden.
</TEXT>
