<SECOND>AM-China-US Demonstrations,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles and St. Paul Rallies Held In Support of China Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 protesters demonstrated Saturday outside the Chinese
Consulate in Los Angeles and about 300 people gathered in St. Paul,
Minn., to support the flagging protests for political reform in
China.
   In New York, actors Mike Farrell and Ed Asner and Detroit Bishop
Thomas J. Gumbleton were among those who signed a statement
supporting the right of students and workers in China to strike for
democracy.
   The statement from nearly 60 activists was sent via facsimile
machine to students, the Chinese government and to President Bush,
according to a release Friday by Voters for a Nuclear Free New York.
   Philip Lam, an organizer of the Los Angeles demonstration, said
a 24-hour hunger strike began at noon. Participants were students
from local universities.
   In St. Paul, the rally at Como Park was held by the Minnesota
chapter of the Organization for Chinese Americans.
   Members of the organization said they urged the United States to
grant temporary asylum to Chinese students and scholars who are
studying in America. They say they fear that those who oppose the
Chinese government's policies may face persecution when they return
to China.
   Sympathy protests have erupted in several U.S. cities since the
historic occupation of Beijing's Tiananmen Square began two weeks
ago.
   Student leaders of the protest movement in China have proposed
that demonstrators hold one more rally this week and then end the
occupation.
   The leaders said it was time to change tactics in their push for
greater freedom and an end to official corruption. But they said
protesters in Tiananmen Square, whose numbers have fallen sharply
to about 10,000, would have the final say on ending the sit-in.
</TEXT>
