<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Politics     05-27 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Politics,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaders Try To Mediate Government Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's president on Friday asked former Premier
Giovanni Spadolini to try to mediate an end to a week-old political
crisis that seemed likely to continue beyond President Bush's
three-day visit.
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita, a Christian Democrat, resigned as the
head of a 13-month government last Friday after repeated attacks by
the Socialists, one of his allies in the five-party coalition.
   A few hours before Bush's arrival Friday, President Francesco
Cossiga asked Spadolini to talk with party leaders and find a way
to solve the crisis brought on De Mita's resignation. Cossiga, as
head of state, is charged with picking someone to try to form
Italy's 49th postwar government.
   The Christian Democrats had sought to have De Mita succeed
himself as premier. That would have enhanced De Mita's position in
talks with Bush and at the NATO summit next week in Brussels.
   But there have been indications Socialist leader Bettino Craxi
was opposed to another De Mita-led government.
   Craxi has accused De Mita of failing to demonstrate leadership.
   Spadolini said after his meeting with Cossiga that he would
begin his consultations on Wednesday after De Mita returns from
Brussels.
   His appointment as mediator marked the ninth time that an
Italian president has given a prominent politician the so-called
``exploratory mandate'' for resolving a government crisis.
   Spadolini, 63, was premier from June 28, 1981, until Aug. 7,
1982 and from Aug. 23, 1982 until Nov. 11, 1982. He was the first
non-Christian Democrat premier since 1945. He has been the
president of the Senate since July 1987.
</TEXT>
