<FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-89 0038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Anti-DiscriminationLawsuit     05-27 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-Discrimination Lawsuit,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Says Anti-Discrimination Rule Violates Free Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A graduate student has sued the University of
Michigan claiming that its new anti-discrimination policy violates
his First Amendment right to free speech.
   The American Civil Liberties Union of Michigan filed the
complaint Thursday in U.S. District Court in Detroit on behalf of a
graduate student in psychology, who wished to remain anonymous.
   The university introduced the policy in 1988 in response to a
series of racial incidents that included the broadcast of racially
offensive jokes on a campus radio station in 1987 and distribution
of anti-black leaflets.
   The plaintiff is a specialist in behavioral psychology and fears
punishment if he discusses some of his theories in class, said ACLU
attorney Robert Sedler said.
   ``Under the university's policy ... the expression of ideas
concerning the superiority or inferiority of members of one sex
over the other or of members of one race over another, as a result
of biopsychological differences, would be considered to be
`discriminatory harassment,''' the complaint said.
   The Policy on Discrimination and Discriminatory Harassment by
Students in the University Environment prohibits ``any behavior,
verbal or physical, that stigmatizes or victimizes an individual on
the basis of race, ethnicity, religion, sex, sexual orientation,
creed, national origin, ancestry, age, marital status, handicap or
Vietnam-era veteran status.''
   The case would have important implications for other schools
that have anti-discrimination policies, said Howard Simon,
executive director of the ACLU of Michigan.
   The University of Wisconsin at Madison and The University of
Massachusetts at Amherst are considering introducing
anti-discrimination plans.
   ``Our suit may serve as an important precedent,'' Simon said.
``If we can prevail and redirect the University of Michigan's
efforts to deal with racism and sexism, it will have an influential
effect on other universities.''
   Walter Harrison, executive director of university relations,
said Michigan has always sought to preserve First Amendment rights.
   ``When we crafted the anti-discrimination policy, we gave
careful consideration to the First Amendment, which we consider to
be essential to the successful operation of the university,''
Harrison said.
   ACLU officials called the policy excessively broad, making any
offensive speech the target of disciplinary action.
   ``You do not address the problem of racism by attacking the
Constitution and the First Amendment,'' Simon said. ``If there is
any institution in the country where controversial, in fact
outrageous and even offensive, ideas ought to be aired, analyzed,
evaluated and debated, it ought to be a university.''
   The policy addresses only the symptoms and not the disease of
racism, Simon said.
   ``If all the racist fliers and jokes and sexually offensive
fliers or jokes are eliminated from the campus of the University of
Michigan, that does not mean racism and sexism will be
eliminated,'' he said.
   The university has 30 days to respond to the lawsuit, Sedler
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890527-0138 </DOCNO>
