<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     05-27 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0631</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bridge collapsed minutes after an engineer
recommended closing it, and the rain-swollen river below swept away
at least two vehicles. Flooding elsewhere in Ohio left one child
dead and hundreds out of their homes.
   Police could not say how many people were in the cars, but all
the occupants were feared dead in Friday's accident. No bodies or
cars had been recovered by early today.
   ``The car in front of us just dropped straight down,'' said
Sharon Boebinger, who was waiting to cross the bridge when it
started collapsing. ``I said, `Oh my God.' I put it in reverse and
backed up. I didn't feel the bridge shake at all. It just happened
in an instant.''
   Lt. Col. Ramon Hoffbauer of the Hamilton County sheriff's office
was asked if anyone could have survived the plunge.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain has been hit by a series of strikes in
recent months recalling the pre-Thatcher days of national walkouts
that helped bring down a Labor Party government.
   But experts say the scenario is very different from the ``Winter
of Discontent'' of 1978-79 when public service workers paralyzed
much of the country. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative Party ousted the socialists in May 1979 on a wave of
anti-union sentiment.
   Experts predict the strikes will eventually subside after a
current round of wage negotiations. Although there are concerns the
walkouts could lead to higher wages and prices, their impact will
be limited by Mrs. Thatcher's union-curbing laws, they say.
   Repeated one-day walkouts by subway workers and bus drivers have
forced millions of Londoners to walk to work. The British
Broadcasting Corp. has canceled or cut live television and radio
programs because of brief strikes by employees for higher pay.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is a glimmer of hope as AT&amp;T and union
negotiators race against a contract deadline at midnight tonight,
but little progress is reported on the issue of health benefits,
described by one source as ``the major block to a settlement.''
   Both sides are expressing optimism at reaching new contracts
before existing pacts affecting about 160,000 workers expire at
11:59 p.m. EDT. But they say such a development hinges on a major
breakthrough on the benefits package, which has dominated the talks
from the outset.
   ``If we can settle health care _ no easy task _ then we can
reach agreement on wages and the other issues,'' a union source
said late Friday. ``This is the major block to a settlement.''
   Sources close to the negotiations said progress has been made
but they cautioned that negotiations are at a fragile stage and
could turn for the worse. In an arrangement likely to be repeated
today, formal negotiating committees met Friday at a Washington
hotel while the two union presidents and AT&amp;T's top negotiator held
separate meetings periodically on the major issues.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing concerns of residents fearful of crime
and addicts in their neighborhoods, former first lady Nancy Reagan
just said no to plans for a drug rehabilitation center that would
bear her name.
   Mrs. Reagan cited local concerns for her decision to abandon the
$10 million Nancy Reagan Center for Drug Rehabilitation, a
